<HEADLINE> Iraq Finishes Distribution Plan of Third Phase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Trade Minister Mohammed
Mehdi Saleh said today that Iraq has finished the distribution
plan for the third phase of the Iraq-U.N. oil-for-food program.
</P>
<P>
Saleh told a news conference here that the plan would be
presented to U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan within the next few
days for approval.
</P>
<P>
Iraq announced earlier that it would not sell oil under the
third phase of the deal until the U.N. agrees to its new plan for
distribution of food, medicine and other necessities.
</P>
<P>
Saleh said that he expected Iraqi oil export to resume after
Annan approves the new plan.
</P>
<P>
He said that concerning food supplies, the new plan was
similar to the previous one in items and amounts, and the same
applied to medicine, with particular emphasis on hospital needs
of medical appliance.
</P>
<P>
Saleh noted that the oil-for-food deal which was signed last
year had actually succeeded in funding the United Nations and the
U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) on disarmament in Iraq, but
failed in relieving the suffering of the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
He said Iraq has demanded no increase in oil exports for the
third phase, well aware that any such expansion will not attend
to the wants of the Iraqis.
</P>
<P>
Saleh confirmed that Iraq had received none of the supplies or
equipment ordered for electricity, agriculture, water
purification, primary and higher education and municipality
sectors. He said that only 17 percent of the contracted medicine
had arrived in Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
