<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-21 16:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GCC Summit Agrees on Political Issues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, December 21 (Xinhua) -- The ongoing summit of the
Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) today agreed on the political
issues which will be touched in its final communique, sources
close to the summit said.
</P>
<P>
The final communique of the summit may include political issues
such as ties between GCC member states with Iran, situations in
Iraq and the Middle East peace process, according to the sources.
</P>
<P>
They said the leaders of the six GCC Arab states have formed a
joint stand on relations with Iran.
</P>
<P>
The final communique is expected to call on Iran to solve its
dispute with the United Arab Emirates (UAE) on the three islands
of Greater Tunb, Lesser Tunb and Abu Musa in the Gulf by peaceful
means, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Iran has been making efforts to improve the relations with its
Arab neighbors. The Islamic summit held on December 9-11 in Iran
set a stage for it to push for the goal. Iran's President Mohammed
Khatami expressed readiness last week to visit the UAE to discuss
the dispute.
</P>
<P>
The GCC, a regional political, economic and defense alliance,
opened its 18th summit here Saturday, which was attended by the
heads of state of Kuwait, Saudi Arabia, the UAE, Bahrain, Qatar
and Oman.
</P>
<P>
The final communique will urge Iraq to comply with the United
Nations Security Council resolutions to eliminate all its weapons
of mass destruction, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, they said, GCC leaders have agreed it is necessary
to lift the crippling economic sanctions imposed by the U.N. on
Iraq after its 1990 invasion of Kuwait to alleviate the sufferings
of the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
The Middle East peace process will be highlighted in the final
communique, according to the sources, who said that GCC leaders
will call on the international community to take a firm stance
toward Israel's intransigent policy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
