<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Foreign Minister Arrives in Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEL AVIV, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice Premier and
Foreign Minister Qian Qichen arrived in Tel Aviv today for a
three-day official visit to Israel at the invitation of his
Israeli counterpart David Levy.
</P>
<P>
In a written statement issued at the airport, Qian said, "since
the establishment of diplomatic ties five years ago, the friendly
relationship between China and Israel has been developed smoothly,
the mutual understanding has constantly been deepened and
cooperation scope has been expanded day by day."
</P>
<P>
He said "more exchange of visits by leaders of the two
countries under the current new international situation would be
conducive to the enhancement of friendship between our two
peoples and to the improvement of friendly cooperation between our
two countries."
</P>
<P>
Qian said, "both Chinese and the Jewish nationalities have
long histories and splendid cultures, which have made great
contributions to the civilization and progress of the mankind."
</P>
<P>
The further development of the relations between China and
Israel is not only in accordance with fundamental interests of the
two peoples, but also in the interest of peace and developments of
the region and the world at large, he added.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, he would meet and have talks with
Israeli Deputy Prime Minister and Foreign Minister David
Levy. They would exchange views on bilateral relations, the
Middle East peace process and other issues of mutual concern.
</P>
<P>
Qian believed that his visit would further promote mutual
understanding and the already friendly ties between China and
Israel.
</P>
<P>
This is Qian's second visit to Israel. He last came in 1992
when the two countries established diplomatic relations.
</P>
<P>
Israel is the third leg of Qian's current Middle East tour
which has already taken him to Lebanon and Syria. Qian will
continue his trip to the Palestinian self-rule areas and
Egypt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
