<HEADLINE> Envoy: US Continues to Pursue Diplomatic Solution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 21 (Xinhua) -- A senior U.S. diplomat said
today that the United States, while having not ruled out military
action, continues to pursue a diplomatic resolution to the
standoff with Iraq over access for U.N. inspectors to suspected
weapons sites.
</P>
<P>
"Right now we believe that through diplomacy, through Security
Council resolution, through a united allied response, that has
worked," U.S. envoy to the United Nations Bill Richardson said on
the NBC program "Meet the Press."
</P>
<P>
"That's what we're continuing to pursue but patience is
eventually going to run out," Richardson added.
</P>
<P>
He said there are weapons of mass destruction in Iraq and
"there has to be full access to all sites including the
presidential sites."
</P>
<P>
But Iraq has banned the U.N. Special Commission in charge of
dismantling the country's weapons of mass destruction from checking
presidential sites. On Saturday, Iraqi officials denied that any
weapons were hidden in the so-called presidential sites.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. envoy threatened that military force has not been
ruled out and such actions could be conducted under existing UN
resolutions.
</P>
<P>
"We have said we have not ruled any options out, including the
military option," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
