<DOCNO> XIE19971222.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Student Leader Calls for National </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 21 (Xinhua) -- A Zimbabwean student leader
today urged the government has to take initiatives to forge real
national unity based on cordial race and tribal relations at
grassroot level.
</P>
<P>
Gabriel Shumba, President of the Student Representative
Council of the University of Zimbabwe said, December 22 is Zimbabwe's
first National Unity Day. The government should institute
reconciliatory programs in primary schools to allow children to
respect other tribes and races.
</P>
<P>
Tomorrow Zimbabweans will celebrate the signing of the Unity
Accord in 1987 between the former Zimbabwe African National
Union-Patriotic Front (ZANU-PF) led by President Robert Mugabe
and the Patriotic Front-Zimbabwe African People's Union (PF-ZAPU)
headed then by the now Vice-President Joshua Nkomo.
</P>
<P>
The accord brought to an end years of conflict between the
government forces and dissidents loyal to the former PF-ZAPU.
</P>
<P>
"We hail the unity accord signed between the two veteran
politicians but this kind of unity has to come also from the
grassroot level. It has only been unity for the top leaders when
in fact there is a lot of animosity among the ordinary citizens,"
said Shuma.
</P>
<P>
Children need to be taught that we are all equal so that when
they become national leaders they will not be biased towards
their own tribe or race, he said.
</P>
<P>
Evidence at most of the country's institutions of higher
learning showed that there was no real unity, especially between
the Shona and the Ndebele speakers.
</P>
<P>
It is imperative for the government to also look into the
issue of development in various provinces in the country.
</P>
<P>
"Of late we have noticed that some areas are better developed
than others and this does not go down well with some people who
think other provinces are being favored so development should be
at par to avoid further straining relations," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971222.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Air Traffic Controllers Hold Strike in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's air traffic control
officers and cadets today started a work stoppage in demand of
salary increments, leaving travelers hoping to reach various
holiday destinations stranded.
</P>
<P>
Although other airlines were landing and leaving the Harare
International Airport, air Zimbabwe officials at the airport said,
only one of its planes had landed from Bulawayo, the country's
second largest city by Sunday afternoon and other domestic
airports were closed.
</P>
<P>
The air control officers and cadets reported for duty but were
not working.
</P>
<P>
Last week they threatened to strike to press the Ministry of
Transport and Energy and the Public Service Commission (PSC) to
hike their salaries.
</P>
<P>
Their salaries have been increased by 200 percent in the past
two years.
</P>
<P>
The PSC on Saturday warned the officers to refrain from their
work stoppage or face dismissal or suspension. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971222.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spain to Help Train Mozambican Police </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Spain will help train
Mozambican police for professional knowledge starting from next
March.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique's Police Training Program will be implemented on
March 15, 1998 through a training course coordinated by the
United Nations, with lectures given by the Spanish civil guards.
</P>
<P>
The news was announced by Luis Fernandez, Secretary General
for the Spanish Agency of International Cooperation, the
Mozambique News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Repairs for the barracks which are to house the police had
been completed, said Fernandez.
</P>
<P>
Under the program, the courses will be given by Spanish civil
guards who had already arrived in Maputo six months ago.
</P>
<P>
The budget for the program is about 30 million U.S. dollars,
with Spain being one of the major donors.
</P>
<P>
Mozambique has about 20,000 policemen, 36 percent of which
are illiterate, while less than 20 percent have received
professional training or have certain professional knowledge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971222.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF New Outlook Lowers Global Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 21 (Xinhua) -- In considering the impact
brought by the economic and financial chaos in Southeast Asia, the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) today lowered its projections
for the global growth in 1997 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
In its Interim Assessment of the World Economic Outlook
officially published here Sunday, the IMF revised almost all
previous October projections for the global economic growth.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest assessment, the global economic growth
is pegged at 4.1 percent, 0.1 percent lower from the October
projection. IMF also projects a 3.5 percent growth in 1998, a 0.8
percent chop from the previous projection.
</P>
<P>
For the world's most industrialized G-7 nations which include
the United States, Japan, Germany, France, Italy, the United
Kingdom and Canada, the economic growth could pick up by 2.8
percent in 1997, no change from the October projection, but they
are expected to grow by a 2.3 percent in 1998, 0.2 percent lower
from the previous projection.
</P>
<P>
As for the developing countries as a whole, their growth in
1997 is projected at 5.9 percent as against 6.2 percent in the
October projection. They may grow by a 4.9 percent in 1998, 1.3
percent lower from the October projection. Of the Asian countries,
Thailand, Indonesia, Malaysia and Philippines, all members of the
ASEAN, are projected to have a 4.0 percent growth in 1997 and 1.7
percent in 1998, which represent 1.6 and 3.7 percent lower
respectively from the October projection.
</P>
<P>
The economic and financial crisis that rocked Southeast Asia in
July 1997 has continued to deepen and broaden since the IMF's
October 1997 World Economic Outlook was written, the IMF report
said. As investor sentiment toward the emerging market countries
has deteriorated, not only has the crisis spread to several other
economies in Asia, but spillover effects have felt throughout the
global financial system.
</P>
<P>
The crisis has brought downward pressure on the currencies of
countries perceived as vulnerable---typically those countries
whose competitive positions have deteriorated as a result of the
large currency depreciations in southeast Asia, those that exhibit
potentially unsustainable current account deficits, and
especially those that have relied excessively on short-term
borrowing, the report noted.
</P>
<P>
Since last Summer, some Asian nations have undertaken a series
of rigid adjustment programs with assistance from the
international institutions and other countries. At present, it is
far from clear that market turbulence has ended, and more
uncertainty than usual applied to any assessment of the most
likely future course of developments. If everything goes well,
1999 will witness gradual pickup in some affected nations in the
wake of significant slowdown in growth in 1998, even though the
upturn may not be quite as rapid as the V-shaped recovery
experienced by Mexico and Argentina following their 1994-95
crisis. If policy and reform efforts are inadequate, the IMF
warned, the crisis of confidence may persist and continue to
spread to other emerging market countries. In that case, there
would be more serious implications for financial flows to these
countries for a more extended period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
