<DOCNO> XIE19971222.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Floods Force Prices Rise in Dar es Salaam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Prices of food and
other commodities in the Tanzanian capital of Dar es Salaam have
gone up because of transportation problems brought about by
floods.
</P>
<P>
Floods caused by above-average seasonal rains over the past
three weeks have wreaked havoc on bridges, roads and railways,
making it difficult to transport food.
</P>
<P>
Most staple food and vegetable prices in the Dar es Salaam
markets have increased by a large margin from two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
At Kinodoni Cemetery Market tomatoes and onions have run
short, with a kilogram of each variety go at around 1,000
shillings (about 1.6 US Dollars) compared to 500 shillings sold
two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
"The rains have made transportation of tomatoes and onions
from the producing areas difficult and expensive," Saidi Rajab, a
vegetable vendor, said at the market on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Price of rice at Kinodoni, Kisutu and Ilala markets currently
range from 450 to 700 shillings, against 350-600 shillings two
weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
Price of Irish potatoes has risen from 150 to 300 shillings
per kilogram. Price hikes of other vegetables are: carrots, from
500 to 800 shillings, and green beans, from 800 to 1,500
shillings.
</P>
<P>
Prices of chicken have shot from 1,000 to 1,600 shillings per
kilogram and steak from 1,400 to 2,000 shillings.
</P>
<P>
"This Christmas is going to be the most difficult one as
everything seems to be too expensive," a customer, named Ana
John, lamented at the Ilala market.
</P>
<P>
Christmas tree which was sold between 1,000 and 7,000
shillings last year, is priced between 2,000 and 10,000 shillings
at present.
</P>
<P>
Extensive damage of roads, bridges and railways by floods have
also hindered transportation of cargo from the capital to
upcountry areas. Several regions in the country are likely to
face acute shortage of fuel, with 30 fuel tank wagons being
stranded in Dar es Salaam, said Rogart Kisanga, Tanzania Railways
Corporation Acting Director General. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
