<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sierra Leonean Army Officers Get Promotions from </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Leader of Sierra Leone's
military junta Major Johnny Paul Koroma, who is also
commander-in-chief, has approved a number of promotions in the
military.
</P>
<P>
A report reaching here today quoted military sources in
Freetown as saying that 13 lieutenant-colonels were promoted to
the rank of colonels, while at least seven majors were upgraded
to lieutenant-colonels.
</P>
<P>
Two brigadiers were also appointed on Saturday, increasing the
number to four, with dozens of privates and other ranks being
promoted, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The promotion came after the cabinet reshuffle in the military
government on Monday, when three ministers were dropped.
</P>
<P>
It also followed at the heels of Koroma's statement of delay
to hand over power to the civilian government led by President
Ahemd Tejan Kabbah who was ousted in the military coup on May 25
this year.
</P>
<P>
Koroma, who agreed to step down by April 22 next year, said
Friday that he was unlikely to honor the deadline for the
handover because of delay in the disarmament process and
distribution of relief goods by the international community.
</P>
<P>
Koroma's move to reconstitute the cabinet and promote military
officers is seen by observers here as a step to consolidate
internal solidarity for a longer stay.
</P>
<P>
They are expecting more actions from west African countries to
deal with the situation in Sierra Leone as leaders of the
countries have called on the junta to adhere to the peace plan.
</P>
<P>
They also appealed to the United Nations to deploy military
observer's mission in the troubled country to monitor the
disarmament of the country's combatants, including the national
army.
</P>
<P>
The sub-regional peacekeeping force has also been mandated to
close the airstrip of an airport in Sierra Leone, which is said
to be used by the junta for importing arms and other supplies in
violation of the sub-regional and U.N. sanctions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
