<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Rules out Dismantling Jewish Settlement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu reiterated today that Israel will not evacuate
any Jewish settlement in the Palestinian territories in the final
settlement.
</P>
<P>
Briefing the cabinet on his meeting with U.S. Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright in Paris Thursday, Netanyahu said that
Israel's policy against dismantling settlements is very clear.
</P>
<P>
While the cabinet meeting was going on this morning, hundreds
of Jewish settlers gathered outside the prime minister's office
protesting against U.S. pressure on Israel to stop expanding
settlements.
</P>
<P>
The protesters later marched to the U.S. consulate in East
Jerusalem continuing their demonstration.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu told the cabinet that the U.S. government now has
greater understanding of Israel's security needs and its demands
for maintaining the peace process based on fulfilling the
commitments by both the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) and
Israel.
</P>
<P>
He said he does not plan to hold a three-way meeting with
Albright and PNA President Yasser Arafat next month as proposed by
Washington.
</P>
<P>
Instead, he said he wants U.S. President Bill Clinton to meet
separately with him and Arafat in a bid to advance the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that he agrees with Albright that U.S. special
envoy Dennis Ross visits the Middle East early next month to
continue U.S. peace mediation.
</P>
<P>
On the second redeployment in the West Bank, Netanyahu assured
the cabinet that his meeting with Albright has been conducted
according to the original plan.
</P>
<P>
He was referring to his promise that he will not talk with
Albright about the specific percentage of the pullback, which will
be set by the cabinet after more deliberations.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli cabinet has held several sessions to formulate the
second redeployment and guidelines for the Israeli-Palestinian
final talks, but failed to produce an agreement due to division of
security arrangements in the West Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
