<HEADLINE> Egypt Postpones Launch of First Satellite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Egypt will launch into orbit its
first satellite, NILESAT, in April 1998 instead of February, the
Middle East News Agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Information Minister Safwat Al Sherif attributed the delay to
reprogramming and refueling the French-made satellite to make it
operate for 15 years instead of 12 years.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the Political Club of the National Democratic Party,
the minister said the Egyptian satellite will have "specialized
channels for children, the family recreation and sports."
</P>
<P>
According to press reports, NILESAT will combine 12 channels,
with each airing six programs simultaneously through digital
technology. Some channels will specialize in news coverage, women,
drama and music.
</P>
<P>
Ground facilities necessary for the operation of the NILESAT
have been completed at the October 6 City in southern Cairo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
