<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-21 20:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt FM Deplores Ill Turns in Ties With Qatar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa today deplored the current events between "sisterly
countries" Egypt and Qatar, warning that Arab solidarity should
not be affected therefor.
</P>
<P>
"What is taking place unfortunately is against the correct norm
of relations and against the ethics and courtesy of dealings," he
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
He said the situation should be "dealt with adequately" without
affecting the global Arab relationship which should remain safe
and sound "regardless of intended or unintended misbehavior of
some."
</P>
<P>
"Egypt is dealing with this issue calmly to safeguard the
fundamental image of Arab relations," he said, adding that going
against this framework constitutes an exception in Arab ties and
should be dealt with accordingly.
</P>
<P>
In a latest show of grudge against Qatar, Egypt told the small
Gulf emirate Saturday that its nationals who want to go to Egypt
must apply for entry visas in advance starting from today.
</P>
<P>
Previously, Qataris could obtain entry visas after they
arrived in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Observers here said the change indicated that the two countries
failed to improve their relations despite the mediation of Saudi
Arabia earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and Qatar's Emir Sheikh Hamad
Bin Khalifa al-Thani held talks in Riyadh, capital of Saudi
Arabia, early this month in a bid to end a war of words between
the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Relations between them deteriorated in October when Egypt was
ready to boycott the fourth Middle East and North African economic
conference in Doha last month.
</P>
<P>
Qatar responded with a ban on the entry of Egyptian nationals
alongside other nine countries as a security precaution for the
Doha conference, infuriating Cairo and other Arab neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Adding fuel to their row, Qatar charged Egypt had plotted the
1996 coup attempt to topple the Qatari government. Cairo denied
the charges and demanded for an explanation.
</P>
<P>
After the talks of their heads of state, both Egypt and Qatar
claimed that their relations were back to normal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971222.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-21 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwait Defends Foreign Military Presence in Gulf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Kuwaiti Information
Minister Sheikh Saud Nasser Al-Sabah today defended foreign
military presence in the Gulf region.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting with editors and reporters of Egyptian media on
the sidelines of the Gulf Cooperation Council summit, the minister
stressed that the existence of the western troops in the Gulf
region was a result of the Iraqi invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
He said that "we were against this presence before the invasion
but now it has its justifications."
</P>
<P>
Kuwait remains wary of its northern neighbor's ambitions in
the region after Iraqi troops occupied it for seven months until
February 1991 when they were expelled by U.S.-led coalition
forces in the Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
The United States has stockpiled military hardware in a
camp 25 kilometers west of Kuwait City, which is used by a
rotating battalion of about 1,500 troops. It also has planes
stationed in Kuwait and Saudi Arabia that patrol the no-fly
zone over southern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
During the stand-off between Iraq and the U.S. last month, the
U.S. raised its military presence in the Gulf to include two
aircraft carriers with about 200 F-14 and F-16 fighters.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait has conducted dozens of joint military exercises with
its western allies on its territories and waters since the end of
the Gulf War within the framework of defense agreements signed
between Kuwait and the U.S., Britain and France.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Saud said that the GCC should have a robust force
that would be able to defend itself from foreign attacks.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed hope that joint aviation authorities and
defense systems would be established among the GCC states of
Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, the United Arab Emirates, Bahrain, Qatar
and Oman. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971222.0026 </DOCNO>
