<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cohen: U.S. Seeks More Pressure to End Iraq Standoff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 21 (Xinhua) -- The United States Defense
Secretary William Cohen said today that his nation pursues
diplomatic channels to pressure Iraq to allow U.N. inspectors
access to suspected weapons sites.
</P>
<P>
"We hope to pursue this in diplomatic channels and see if we
can't exhaust all reasonable opportunities to do that," Cohen said
on the CBS program "Face the Nation".
</P>
<P>
Iraq has banned the U.N. Special Commission in charge of
dismantling the country's weapons of mass destruction from
checking presidential sites. It insists that no weapons are
hidden at those locations.
</P>
<P>
Iraq said that it would never allow any inspection to its
presidential sites, which it regards as vital to its national
security and sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
But Cohen said this was "simply an intolerable position" and
the United Nations Security Council would hopefully send a
resounding signal that "it is unacceptable and there is no
division among Security Council members."
</P>
<P>
Cohen and National Security Adviser Sandy Berger, speaking on
ABC's "This Week" program, would not rule out that the United
States would resort to military options to force Iraqi leader
Saddam Hussein to comply.
</P>
<P>
"I think the president has said he's ruled nothing in, ruled
nothing out," Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that Saddam Hussein backs away from this, if not, we
may have to go to further options and the President indicated that
no options are off the table," Berger added.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, U.S. envoy to the United Nations Bill Richardson also
made a similar statement on this issue. He said the United States
was continuing to pursue diplomatic solutions on the access to
Iraq's weapons sites, but "We have said we have not ruled any
options out, including the military option." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971222.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-21 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 5 PKK Rebels Killed in Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Turkish security forces today
killed five rebels of the outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK) in
southern area bordering Syria, the state-owned TRT television
station reported.
</P>
<P>
The militants were killed in a clash after being spotted by an
infrared camera while crossing a minefield at the border in
Turkey's Ceypanpinar district of Sanliurfa province, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
It added that the rebels were infiltrating into Turkey from
Syria, which Turkey has accused of backing the PKK and allowing
them to cross the border.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting since 1984 for autonomy in eastern
and southeastern Turkey, which has claimed more than 28,000
lives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
