<HEADLINE> HK Stock Market to See More China Participation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The market weight of the
China-related enterprises on the Stock Exchange of Hong Kong
(SEHK) will continue to grow despite the current slowdown of
initial public offers caused by the Asian financial turmoil.
</P>
<P>
Alec Tsui, chief executive of the SEHK, said at a press
conference here Monday that he expected sustainable growth of the
number of China-related companies to be listed on the Hong Kong
bourse.
</P>
<P>
"It is anticipated that the capital needs of China will
continue to grow in the latest round of restructuring of
state-owned enterprises announced at the 15th Party Congress," he
told the 1997 year-end press briefing.
</P>
<P>
During the year, 15 state-owned enterprises or H-shares were
listed in Hong Kong, raising a total capital of 28.625 billion HK
dollars (3.7 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Till now, 39 H-shares and more than 50 red chips
(China-affiliated and Hong Kong-registered companies) have gone
public on the SEHK. Their total market capitalization accounted
for about 18 percent of the total of the Hong Kong market as at
the end of November 1997, rising steadily from around ten percent
a year before.
</P>
<P>
Looking into 1998, Tsui said: "The China dimension will
continue to be one of our major focuses." The SEHK will add
resources to its China team to strengthen its services to issuers
in the inland areas, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
