<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Communists Call for End of NATO, Removal of US Bases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Italian Communist Refoundation
Secretary Fausto Bertinotti Monday morning called for an end to
NATO and the removal of American bases from the Italian territory.
</P>
<P>
Bertinotti's remarks followed an interview published in Monday's
edition of the Turin daily La Stampa in which party Chairman
Armando Cossutta said that there was no longer any need for NATO
or justification for American bases in Italy.
</P>
<P>
"I agree with Cossutta," Bertinotti said, "This position has
already been adopted by our party congress. We are for the
dissolving of NATO because there is no reason, if there was one,
for this military alliance to exist."
</P>
<P>
The removal of American bases, he added, would allow Italy to
"regain its national sovereignty".
</P>
<P>
Cossutta, in his interview, did not go so far as to say that
there never was a reason for NATO's existence but observed, "While
it may be true, but not necessarily, that there were once possible
dangers from the Eastern Bloc, today all that does not
exist. There is no justification for keeping American bases in
Italy, because they are bases of a foreign power which,
theoretically, could be used for purposes unknown to us and in
contrast to Italian foreign policy. We could find ourselves in
very uncomfortable situations."
</P>
<P>
Cossutta also called for a new role for the United Nations,
which can have a military structure once the Security Council has
been reformed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
