<HEADLINE> Turkey Expels Greek Diplomat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Foreign Ministry
announced today that a Greek diplomat had been asked to leave
Turkey due to his involvement in espionage.
</P>
<P>
"One of the administrative officials working in the Greek
consulate in Istanbul was found engaged in activities uncompatible
with his status," Foreign Ministry spokesman Sermet Atacanli said
at a press briefing.
</P>
<P>
Atacanli said the Greek diplomat, whose name was not disclosed,
would have to leave Turkey within a week.
</P>
<P>
Greece had reportedly denied Turkey's accusation.
</P>
<P>
Local reports said earlier that Military Attache Efstratios
Haralambous in Greek Embassy in Ankara and the aforesaid diplomat
had been accused of spying for Turkey's outlawed Kurdish Workers'
Party (PKK).
</P>
<P>
The spokesman, however, did not comment on the reports about
the Greek military attache.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has been criticizing Greece for allegedly providing
political, financial and military support to the PKK.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting a war against the government in
eastern and southeastern Turkey since 1984 for an independent
Kurdish state in the area.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Greece, both members of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization, have long been at odds due to disputes of air space,
territorial conflicts of some islands in the Aegean Sea, rights to
sea-bed minerals and the Cyprus problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
