<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Working on Basic Social Security System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, December 22 (Xinhua) -- China will try to set up a
social security system for many of its cities and counties in
1998, according to Doji Cering, minister of civil affairs, who
spoke at a national conference of bureau directors of civil
affairs today.
</P>
<P>
This will be put at the top of the Ministry's agenda next year,
he said, and it is expected to be pushed in rural areas as well,
and should take the lowest income levels into account.
</P>
<P>
In 275 cities, or more than 40 percent of the country's total,
the system is in place, and local governments have spent 1.15
billion yuan (about 139 million US dollars) on maintaining a basic
standard of living for more than two million low-income urban
residents.
</P>
<P>
In 997 counties and cities at the county-level, the system is
at a preliminary stage in rural areas. All cities and counties in
Guangdong Province, and over 80 percent of the cities and counties
of Hebei, Henan, Shandong, and Zhejiang Provinces and the Guangxi
Zhuang Autonomous Region have the system in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Doji Cering urged civil affairs departments to encourage
farmers, especially those working in township enterprises, and
people in rich rural areas and who have regular incomes to buy
old-age pension plans next year.
</P>
<P>
These pension plans already exist in more than 2,000 counties,
cities and regions, covering 82 million farmers with 13 billion
yuan, and about 400,000 farmers have already started receiving
pensions.
</P>
<P>
Doji Cering said that another major task for next year is
improving democratic work at the grass-roots level, with focus on
urban neighborhood committees and rural village committees. The
system of self-management is already in place in about 60 percent
of the country's one million villages. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
