The Wall Street Journal
</P>
<P>
-- Clinton's budget may feature 25 billion dollars in new tax
incentives and credits. Administration officials also say the
president's fiscal 1999 plan will include higher spending on
secondary education and a tobacco-tax increase for cancer
research. Tax cuts probably will include incentives for school
construction and breaks to encourage pension programs by small
firms.
</P>
<P>
-- U.S. officials continued to threaten unspecified punitive
measures in an effort to force Iraq to open all sites to U.N.
weapons inspectors, but France, Russia and China indicated they
won't back military action. Baghdad said it will give the U.N. a
food-distribution plan soon as part of the third round of oil
sales it seeks under eased sanctions. 
