<HEADLINE> Chinese, Ukrainian Premiers Hold Talks in Beijing (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Premier Li Peng, in talks with
his Ukrainian counterpart Valery Pustovoitenko today, said the
reason why bilateral relations have gone well is that the two
countries share much in common.
</P>
<P>
He noted that China will work with Ukraine to bring a healthy
and vigorous bilateral relationship to the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
The two prime ministers had an in-depth exchange of views on
bilateral relations and other issues of common concern.
</P>
<P>
Li welcomed Pustovoitenko's visit, the first one to China by a
Ukrainian prime minister since the independence of Ukraine. Li
said he believes that the visit will greatly help further
bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
The two prime ministers voiced satisfaction with bilateral
relations. Li said that bilateral relations have developed well
since the establishment of diplomatic relations.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the heads of state of the two countries exchanged
visits and signed two joint statements, thus laying a legal basis
for the growth of bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Li recalled his visit to Ukraine in June of 1995, during which
he met with Ukrainian President Leonid Kuchma and other leaders to
exchange views on bilateral cooperation. "That visit gave me a
good impression," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that the two countries have set up close
relationship of cooperation featured by mutual respect and trust,
equality, mutual benefit over the past few years. He added that
the two countries have achieved practical results in various fields.
</P>
<P>
Pustovoitenko spoke highly of the visits by Chinese President
Jiang Zemin and Premier Li Peng to Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
He told Li that the two visits gave new impetus to the
development of bilateral relations, and that he was honored to be
the first Ukrainian prime minister to visit China.
</P>
<P>
He said he hopes that his current visit will deepen friendship
and cooperation between the two countries. He added that there
exist no hurdles in developing bilateral relations, stressing that
to further develop relations with China is a set policy of
Ukraine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971222.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese, Ukrainian Premiers Hold Talks in Beijing (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The two leaders expressed the hope that the two countries will
intensify cooperation in the fields of trade, economy, science and
technology.
</P>
<P>
Li said that economic, trade, scientific and technological
cooperation constitutes an important part of bilateral relations,
and that the Chinese side attaches great importance to this aspect.
</P>
<P>
He said that the two countries have their respective advantages
in the economy, and that their economies are highly
complementary. He added that there still exists potential to be
tapped.
</P>
<P>
As long as the two sides work to explore new ways, they will
raise their economic, trade, scientific and technological
cooperation to a new high.
</P>
<P>
Pustovoitenko told Li that one of the purposes of his current
China visit is to increase bilateral economic, trade, scientific
and technological cooperation, and that Ukraine is ready to work
together with China to reinforce bilateral cooperation in these
areas by using concrete measures.
</P>
<P>
Li expressed his appreciation for Ukraine's adherence to the
"one China" stance and not having official contacts with
Taiwan. He also spoke highly of Ukraine's just deeds of
voting for China in two consecutive sessions of the United Nations
commission on human rights. China supports Ukraine's independence,
sovereignty and territorial integrity, Li said.
</P>
<P>
Pustovoitenko extended his congratulations on China's smooth
resumption of exercise of sovereignty over Hong Kong. He said he
believes that this will help solve the Taiwan issue at an early
date.
</P>
<P>
He wished China still greater progress in its reform,
opening-up and modernization drive by implementing policies set by
the 15th National Congress of the Communist Party of China (CPC).
</P>
<P>
Li briefed Ukrainian visitors on China's reform and opening-up,
trans-century development strategies set by the 15th CPC National
Congress, such as ownership issue, transformation of state-owned
enterprises and policies concerning foreign funds and the
construction of China's special economic zones.
</P>
<P>
Pustovoitenko said that Ukraine respects and admires the
achievements China has made in its reform and opening-up drive. He
noted that the political stability of China ensures the smooth
development of the country's reform and opening-up. This is very
important experience. He also briefed Li on Ukraine's domestic
situation.
</P>
<P>
After the talks, the two prime ministers signed a statement on
bilateral economic, trade, scientific and technological
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
They also attended the signing ceremony of an agreement on
customs assistance between the two governments, and a memo of
understanding on cooperation concerning securities supervision.
</P>
<P>
This was followed by their meeting with the press, during which
they briefed media on Sino-Ukrainian relations and their talks.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the talks, Premier Li presided over a welcoming
ceremony for Pustovoitenko.
</P>
<P>
Li also hosted a banquet in honor of Pustovoitenko this
evening. 
</P>
</TEXT>
