<HEADLINE> HK Telecommunication License Approved for AsiaSat 3 Satellite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The
Chief-Executive-in-Council of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (HKSAR) has approved the granting of a license to a
company registered in Hong Kong for operating radiocommunications
equipment on board a communications satellite.
</P>
<P>
The license also allows Asia Satellite Telecommunications
Company Limited (AsiaSat) to establish a satellite station in Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
The company has contracted Hughes Space and Communications
International of the United States to manufacture the satellite
AsiaSat 3 and deliver it into obit, a spokesman of the HKSAR
Economic Services Bureau said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
The satellite will be the sixth launched and operated by a Hong
Kong company since the first one was launched in April 1990.
</P>
<P>
Hughes has arranged for AsiaSat 3 to be launched later this
month from Baikonur Cosmodrome, which has been leased to Russia by
Kazakhstan.
</P>
<P>
The new satellite will form part of the company's satellite
communications network in the Asia-Pacific region to provide
telecommunications and broadcasting transmission services to the
region.
</P>
<P>
The license granted under the Telecommunication Ordinance is to
enable the company to operate the equipment on board the
satellite and establish and maintain an earth station at Stanley
on Hong Kong Island to control and monitor the satellite, the
spokesman said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971222.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> One More H5N1 Case Reported in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The Department of Health
(DH) announced here Monday one more new suspected Influenza A H5N1
case.
</P>
<P>
The case involves a six-year-old boy who is presently under
treatment and in satisfactory condition.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, an earlier case of a 37-year-old man suspected to be
infected with the H5N1 virus was confirmed Monday.
</P>
<P>
This brings the total number of cases to nine confirmed and two
suspected, a DH statement said.
</P>
<P>
Among the confirmed cases, a three-year-old boy, a 13-year-old
girl and a 54-year-old man have died. Among the six others, two
have recovered and been discharged from hospital and four are
still under treatment.
</P>
<P>
And a three-year-old girl and a six-year-old boy, suspected of
contracting the influenza, are under treatment with conditions
satisfactory, the DH said.
</P>
<P>
The department will issue a daily update of the cases from
Monday on, it announced. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
