<DOCNO> XIE19971222.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Monetary System Withstands Financial Storm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's monetary system
has passed the test of the Asia financial turmoil that has turned
the regional booming panorama upside down into a gloomy scenario.
</P>
<P>
At a year-end press conference here Monday, Joseph Yam, chief
executive of the Hong Kong Monetary Authority (HKMA), summed up
the major work done by the Authority in 1997: "The exchange rate
of Hong Kong remained stable in a year of political transition and
the regional financial turmoil."
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong currency, pegged to the greenback in 1983 at 7.8
HK dollars to one U.S. dollar, has stood firm despite a wave of
speculative attacks, which toppled down many other linked exchange
rate systems in Asia.
</P>
<P>
Since July 2 when the currency crisis broke out in Thailand,
Asian currencies ranging from the Indonesian rupiah to the
Japanese yen have tumbled by between 12 and 53 percent, according
to statistics provided by the HKMA.
</P>
<P>
"The benefit of the linked exchange rate is stability. The peg
has served Hong Kong quite well," said Yam, who has made it his
top priority in 1998 to maintain exchange rate stability.
</P>
<P>
At the press briefing, Yam also announced the latest figure of
Hong Kong's foreign reserves, which hit 96.5 billion U.S. dollars
at the end of November this year, up 5.6 percent from a month
before. Hong Kong remains the world's third largest foreign
reserves holder, after Japan and Chinese mainland.
</P>
<P>
Yam said that the rise in foreign reserves showed that there
was inflow of money into Hong Kong, rather than outflow of capital
as some people said. Actually, money has been attracted to Hong
Kong partly because of the high interest rates, said the HKMA
chief executive.
</P>
<P>
To defend the Hong Kong dollar, interest rates were pushed up,
putting strain on economic activities, especially on stock and
property markets. But the Hong Kong stock market, falling by 24.1
percent from a year earlier, is the least affected by the
financial turbulence compared with other Asian economies, which
slumped by between 32 and 74 percent, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
