<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Remains Top Choice for Equity Investors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 22 (Xinhua) -- In the wake of the Asian
financial storm, Hong Kong will continue to be the No. 1 choice
for global investors who make long commitments to the Asian equity
market, a top official of the Stock Exchange of Hong Kong (SEHK)
said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Alec Tsui, chief executive of the SEHK, told a year-end press
conference: "For those global investors who keep watching on the
Asian market, Hong Kong is still the best place."
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong stock market is still the most open and transparent
in the region," he added.
</P>
<P>
The local stock market has experienced dramatic swings as the
regional financial storm spilled over to Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The 33-member Hang Seng Index tumbled by 24 percent from a year
earlier, to close at 10,172 points Monday, but in August, it
surged to the peak of more than 16,000 points.
</P>
<P>
The year of 1997 registered all the ten highest turnover
records since 1970, ranging from 46 billion HK dollars (5.9
billion U.S. dollars) to 34 billion HK dollars (4.4 billion U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Despite the market volatility, Tsui said that the trading
system at the SEHK, with a capacity of handling a daily turnover
of over 50 billion HK dollars (6.4 billion U.S. dollars), has
withstood the steep price fluctuation and heavy trading volume,
reflecting the state of maturity of the market.
</P>
<P>
As of December 19, 1997, Hong Kong market capitalization hit
3,148 billion HK dollars (404 billion U.S. dollars), down five
percent from a year before but still putting it well into the top
ten stock markets in the world.
</P>
<P>
The annual total turnover as of December 19, 1997 reached 3,761
billion HK dollars (482 billion U.S. dollars), surging
impressively by 174 percent from the previous year. The number of
listed companies rose by 13 percent to 656. 
</P>
</TEXT>
