<HEADLINE> S.Korean Parliament Reviews Financial Bills </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, December 22 (Xinhua) -- South Korea's National Assembly
(parliament) began a seven-day special session Monday afternoon to
review the government-proposed 13 reform bills aimed at improving
the country's ailing finance.
</P>
<P>
Lawmakers are expected to pass the 13 financial bills and eight
other economy-related bills, including two amendments to the
real-name financial transaction system and a revision to laws on
the Bank of Korea (central bank) designed to make it independent
from government.
</P>
<P>
The bills, including one on the creation of a wide-ranging
financial watchdog agency supervising banks, insurance companies
and securities firms, failed to pass the assembly a month ago due
to resistance from the opposition parties.
</P>
<P>
The opposition National Congress for New Politics will become
the ruling party next February as its leader Kim Dae-jung won the
15th presidential election last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
South Korea has signed a 57-billion-dollar agreement with the
International Monetary Fund to bail its finance out of crisis. As
a price, South Korea has to restructure its economy under the
harsh conditions specified in the agreement.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Monday, floor leaders from the three major political
parties -- the Grand National Party, the National Congress for New
Politics and the United Liberal Democrats -- agreed to pass the
reform package at the parliament next Monday in a bid to bring the
country's shaky financial market back on track.
</P>
<P>
South Korea plunged into a serious financial trouble in July
caused by the collapse of a number of conglomerates and large
amounts of bad loans of financial institutions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
