<HEADLINE> China's Chemical Industry Up 8 Percent in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Despite losses in the first
half, China's chemical industry got out of the fix it was in and
is expected to have an annual growth of eight percent, according
to the Minister of Chemical Industry Gu Xiulian.
</P>
<P>
She told a national conference in Beijing that the industry
will have 278 billion yuan in output value and 18 billion yuan in
profits.
</P>
<P>
The chemical sectors of 27 provinces, municipalities and
autonomous regions have all had similar growth in spite of price
hikes in raw materials. The industry managed to turn around in
June and met all of its development goals, Gu said.
</P>
<P>
She said that 23 million tons of urea was produced, up 12
percent on an annual basis, increasing chemical fertilizer output
to 27.2 million tons.
</P>
<P>
Investment in fixed assets is expected to hit 31.8 billion
yuan, and fifteen large and medium-sized chemical projects have
gone into operation.
</P>
<P>
Reforms of state-owned chemical enterprises continued this
year, Gu said, and 48 state-owned enterprises have been listed on
the stock market, raising 15 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The export of chemicals is expected to surpass 15 billion US
dollars, a year-on-year increase of 21 percent, and the import and
export of the chemicals will hit 34 billion US dollars, up 10.7
percent.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that the industry will raise output value to
300 billion yuan next year, while maintaining a growth rate of
eight percent, while exports will be worth 16 billion US dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
