<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bilingual Education A Controversy in California </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Schools in California,
known for its ethnic diversity, have to deal with students
who speak as many as 50 different languages.
</P>
<P>
Chinese is one of these languages. The Chinese communities,
with a tradition of attachment to education, run schools of the
Chinese language. Kids of Chinese origin go to these schools to
learn their native language and culture after English classes
every day or at weekends. The Japanese also run their own schools.
</P>
<P>
The vast majority of limited-English students are those who
speak Spanish. Latinos moved past whites this year to become the
largest racial group in California's public schools -- about 2.2
million, or early 40 percent of the 5.6 million students in
kindergarten through high school. Half of the Latino students
speak little or no English.
</P>
<P>
But Latinos, who once pushed for bilingual education as a civil
right, are now deeply divided over the question of whether young
students who speak little or no English should be taught for years
in Spanish or be prodded to learn English quickly. So are
educators and schools.
</P>
<P>
In a typical school which is intended to replace bilingual
education with a one-year program, taught predominantly in
English, teachers use English most of the time, backed by pictures
and gestures. and once in a while use a few words in the students'
native language. The students are normally transferred to regular
mainstream class after a year.
</P>
<P>
In another typical school, students are taught in their native
language and gradually introduced to English. They often remain in
bilingual education four to seven years before all of their
classes are presented in English.
</P>
<P>
Debates on the merits of both methods have been going on for
years, with both sides citing academic research and anecdotes
about the success of individual students. Sometimes arguments
become emotional and political.
</P>
<P>
Dropout rates are often cited by critics of bilingual
education, which they say contributes to dropouts by leaving
students uncomfortable with English, and thus ill-prepared to do
advanced work in high school courses taught in English. The weekly
news magazine, U.S. News &AMP; World Report, reported last month that
Latino children have the lowest test scores of any ethnic group in
California and the highest dropout rate of 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
Supporters of bilingual education say dropout rates are more
likely to be influenced by factors such as the income and
education level of the family, the amount of reading done at the
home, and how long the family have been in the country.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the 40 percent dropout rate has been proved to be an
overstatement, which at the same time ignores an even higher
dropout rate among blacks, who do not receive bilingual
education. The latest figures from the state's Department of the
Education shows a combined dropout rate of 3.9 percent for all
ethnic groups during the 1995-96 school year. The rate for Latinos
was 5.6 percent, and blacks, 6.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
A teacher said that bilingual education has failed a whole
generation of Hispanic children not only in California but in the
whole country.
</P>
<P>
But another teacher said that bilingual education works,
helping build students' confidence and pride of their heritage.
</P>
<P>
Much of the early opposition to bilingual education warned that
the United States would become another Canada, a divided society
speaking two different languages.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971222.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-22 13:11 </DATE_TIME>
