<HEADLINE> Indonesia Again Imports Rice This Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 22 (Xinhua) -- For the second time since
1994, Indonesia imported rice, a staple in the world's fourth most
populous country, following a long drought and declining stocks in
recent times, a government official confirmed here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Head of the National Logistic Agency (BULOG) Beddu Among said
most of the rice is being imported from Thailand and Vietnam with
the rest from Pakistan, China and India.
</P>
<P>
He refused to disclose the amount of rice imported, saying only
that 50,000 tons of the planned 100,000 tons of rice have arrived.
</P>
<P>
According to Among, the imports are aimed at adding to the
national stocks of rice, which decreased following the massive
market operation in the past three months.
</P>
<P>
By November, BULOG had 2.2 million tons of rice in stock and
now it has 1.6 million tons, a reduction of 150,000 tons per week,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia, formerly the biggest rice importer in the world,
became self-sufficient in rice in 1984. The country first imported
rice in 1994 when rice stocks diminished due to failed harvests.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia imported more than four million tons of rice in 1994,
some of which was shipped early this year. This year's imports are
predicted not to exceed the 1994's as BULOG still had stocks of
1.6 million tons, Among added.
</P>
<P>
According to the Central Statistics Agency, Indonesia's
production of unhusked rice this year will reach some 49 million
tons, equivalent to 31.89 million tons of rice or a decrease of
3.99 percent compared with 1996.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
