<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eurofighter Accord Signed in Bonn </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Britain, Germany, Italy and Spain
signed an accord here Monday formally confirming their
participation in the costly project to build a 21st-century
warplane for Europe.
</P>
<P>
Under the accord signed by German Defense Minister Volker Ruehe and
his counterparts from Britain, George Robertson, Italy, Beniamino
Andreatta and Spain, Eduardo Serra, a total of 620 Eurofighter jets
will be built and delivered to the four nations between 2002 and 2014.
</P>
<P>
Britain is buying 232 Eurofighters, Germany 180, Italy 121 and
Spain 87. The total cost of the project is estimated at up to 65
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
All four defense ministers attached great importance to the
project, saying that it is not only necessary for their countries'
defense, but will also give a boost to the international
competitiveness of the European aerospace industry and will help
secure several thousands of jobs.
</P>
<P>
Equipped with sophisticated electronics, the Eurofighter can
fly within a range of over 2,500 kilometers with a maximum speed
almost twice the sound speed. Critics however says that the
warplane is unlikely to attract customers outside Europe because
of its stunning prices.
</P>
<P>
The Eurofighter project have also been controversial in Germany
at a time when Bonn is struggling with strict financial austerity
to meet the fiscal requirements for qualifying for the planned
single European currency, the Euro.
</P>
<P>
The purchase of 180 Eurofighters by Bonn would cost about 23
billion marks (13 billion U.S. dollars), the most expensive military
spending by Germany in the post-war era. Despite strong protests from
opposition parties, the German parliament finally approved the project
in November after months of delay.
</P>
<P>
Germany will use the Eurofighter to replace its 171 aging Phantom
jets, 40 Tornados and 23 MiG 29s inherited from former eastern
Germany.
</P>
<P>
The Eurofighter is jointly developed by Germany's Daimler-Benz
Aerospace AG, British Aerospce, Spain's CASA and Italy's Alenia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
