<DOCNO> XIE19971222.0067 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-22 13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Human Rights Body Demands Explanation on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Iran's Islamic Human Rights
Commission (IHRC) has demanded the Iranian Judiciary explain the
reasons behind the arrest of Secretary General of Iran's Freedom
Movement Ebrahim Yazdi.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian official news agency IRNA reported that the IHRC
Sunday evening issued a statement saying it was investigating
Yazdi's arrest and other relevant developments in the country.
</P>
<P>
Yazdi was summoned by the Islamic Revolutionary Court on
December 14 for questioning and was put into Tehran's famous
prison of Evin in the afternoon of the same day, according to a
statement from his Freedom Movement.
</P>
<P>
However, no official charges have been announced against Yazdi
one week after his imprisonment. IRNA quoted an informed source in
the Judiciary as claiming that Yazdi was detained according to law.
</P>
<P>
The Freedom Movement was founded in 1961 by Mehdi Bazargan,
late Iranian prime minister of the interim government formed in
the wake of the 1979 Islamic Revolution.
</P>
<P>
Yazdi, then foreign minister of the interim government, was
elected secretary-general of the movement in January 1985 after
Bazargan passed away.
</P>
<P>
However, the organization was not given formal permission to
carry out activities after the government asked political parties
and organizations to register in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The IHRC also said that it would investigate the recent
political disturbance in the religious city of Qom, some 100
kilometers south of the capital, caused by the controversial
remarks of an Islamic canonist on supreme leadership and some
other cases.
</P>
<P>
It said that the body would follow up the cases to prevent
unlawful acts and counter the perpetrators of any unlawful moves
in accordance with human and legal regulations.
</P>
<P>
On November 19, several hundred religious instructors and
students in Qom attacked the office and residence of Ayatollah
Hussein Ali Montazeri, former designate successor of late Iranian
supreme leader Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini.
</P>
<P>
The disgraced clergyman criticized now supreme leader Ali
Khamenei for interfering in government affairs and advised him to
supervise rather than directly intervene.
</P>
<P>
The IHRC was formed in 1995 after Tehran was accused by Western
countries of violating human rights. During the past two years,
the body issued many statements condemning Western reports on
Iran's human rights status. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
