<DOCNO> XIE19971222.0070 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Sets 1998's Economic Restructuring Goals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XIAMEN, December 22 (Xinhua) -- China will try to make
breakthroughs in restructuring its economy in 1998, State
Councillor Li Tieying, who is in charge of the State Commission
for Restructuring the Economy, told a national conference on
economic restructuring here today.
</P>
<P>
Premier Li Peng sent a letter of congratulations to the
conference.
</P>
<P>
According to Li Tieying, some major tasks for 1998
are: adhering to the reform orientation of the socialist market
economy; improving the ownership structure; speeding up work on
the introduction of a modern enterprise system; making a greater
effort at strategic transformation of the state-owned economy;
resettling redundant workers as part of the re-employment project;
stepping up the reform of the financial system; and improving
macro-economic controls.
</P>
<P>
An effort must also be made to reform the grain and cotton
distribution system and to industrialize agriculture, to work for
institutional restructuring, to improve the way government runs
the economy, to look for a better state asset management system,
and studying reforms of the social security and housing
distribution systems.
</P>
<P>
The State Council is formulating policies that will help bring
most of the large and medium-sized money-losing state enterprises
out of difficulties within the next three years, Li said.
</P>
<P>
In restructuring state enterprises, China will focus on
improving large state enterprises and giving smaller ones more
decision-making power, and incorporating large enterprises and
allowing them to issue stock, he said.
</P>
<P>
The practice of arbitrarily setting up parent companies and
subsidiaries must be stopped, and inter-regional and multinational
enterprises and groups must be encouraged through purchases,
mergers, acquisitions or co-operation.
</P>
<P>
China has more 300,000 state enterprises, some 14,500 of which
are large and medium-sized. Recently, the country has increased
its efforts to restructure state enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Li pointed out that the initiative-based household contract
responsibility system in rural areas will remain unchanged for a
long time, and that China is determined to establish a socialist
market economy by the end of the century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
