<HEADLINE> Indonesian Navy to Join Search for Ill-fated SilkAir </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian Navy Frogman
Unit, supported by a minesweeper ship, will join the search for
wreckage from a SilkAir Boeing 737-300 jet that crashed into Musi
River, Palembang, South Sumatra, Indonesia, last Friday.
</P>
<P>
"Two teams from the Navy's Western Fleet unit have been at the
location to support the search," Unit Commander Lt. Col. Amri
Husaini said here Monday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, according to a statement from the Navy Information
Section, in addition to the divers from the unit, the Navy will
also deploy divers from the Navy's Oceanography Unit.
</P>
<P>
The minesweeper ship is scheduled to arrive at the location
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
An Indonesian warship and sea minesweeper Sunday left the base
in Surabaya along with a tug boat for the location of the plane
crash.
</P>
<P>
The SilkAir 737-300 was flying from Jakarta, capital of
Indonesia, to Singapore when it crashed into Musi River at
Makarti village, Banyuasin subdistrict, South Sumatra, Friday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
All 104 people, 97 passengers and seven crew, are believed
dead.
</P>
<P>
Rescue workers from Indonesia and Singapore have recovered body
parts and fragments from the wreckage since last Friday.
</P>
<P>
The cause of the plane crash, the first in the 50-year
commercial aviation history of Singapore, is still unclear.
</P>
