<HEADLINE> Shanghai Law Designed To Prevent Animal Diseases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai Deputy Mayor Feng
Guoqin has urged local government departments to be fully prepared
to implement the Animal Epidemic Prevention Law of the People's
Republic of China which will come into force on January 1, 1998.
</P>
<P>
Feng said the new law will help guarantee the quality of meat
products for the over 13 million residents in China's largest city
</P>
<P>
Shanghai, a city with a vast market for meat products, will
apply the law to wide-ranging areas. The city produces some 4.6
million hogs, more than 140,000 tons of eggs and over 170 million
head of poultry each year, with the respective figures accounting
for 50 percent, 70 percent and 80 percent of the city's total
market demand for related products. In addition, the city is
self-sufficient in terms of milk production.
</P>
<P>
The existing network of animal prevention centers involving
relevant departments at the city, county, township and village
levels is staffed by over 2,000 veterinarians and animal
quarantine workers.
</P>
<P>
Ten years ago, contaminated clams sparked an outbreak of
Hepatitis A in Shanghai and neighboring areas. The city has since
strictly monitored quarantine activities regarding meat and
seafood since then. 
</P>
</TEXT>
