<HEADLINE> Greenpeace Tries to Block German Nuclear Transport Ship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Seven members of the
international environmental group Greenpeace early Monday blocked
a ferry at the northern German port of Bremerhaven, which was due
to ship plutonium to Scotland for reprocessing.
</P>
<P>
With soldering irons, they attached themselves to the exit ramp
of the ferry Arneb. Port police later came trying to remove the
demonstrators, who also employed three rubber dinghies in the
blockade.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 60 other Greenpeace activists staged a protest on
a bridge at the port, which was heavily guarded by police.
</P>
<P>
Greenpeace said the ship was scheduled to leave Bremerhaven
with 59 kilograms of plutonium during night for Dounreay, Scotland.
</P>
<P>
Authorities said that however, they would still load the ferry
with the radioactive cargo later in the day. The plutonium was
transported by lorry from Hanau, where it had been stored.
</P>
<P>
The plutonium came from a nuclear reactor in Karlsruhe and
would be converted into liquid plutonium nitrate in Scotland
before being enriched into reactor fuel at England's Sellafield
plant.  
</P>
</TEXT>
