<HEADLINE> Pakistan, China Sign MOU on Sports Exchanges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan and China signed
here Monday a memorandum of understanding on sports exchanges to
further develop bilateral cooperation in the sports sector.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed by Sheikh Rashid Ahmad, Pakistani
minister for Culture, Sports, Tourism and Youth Affairs, and Wu
Shaozu, Chinese minister of the Physical Culture and Sports
Commission.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, which remains in effect until December 31,
2000, the two countries will encourage exchange of information in
the fields including sports people, sporting teams, coaches and
sports science personnel.
</P>
<P>
The two sides will also further the planned athlete exchange
between their national sports organization and federations for
training and competion.
</P>
<P>
To improve the standards of sports, both sides also agreed to
promote the exchange of sports science personnel, collaboration in
applied research and invitations for scientific seminars and
professional workshops.
</P>
<P>
Rashid Ahmad said Pakistan and China enjoy good relations not
only in economic and cultural sectors but also in sports sector,
hoping that the agreement will further consolidate and promote the
existing friendly and cooperative relations in the sports sector.
</P>
<P>
Wu Shaozu, also president of the Chinese Olympic Committee,
said the signing of the agreement has laid a new foundation to
enhance sports exchanges between China and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
The delegation, led by Wu Shaozu, arrived in Lahore, Pakistan's
second largest city last Friday, on a seven-day visit, including a
stop in Pakistan's southern city of Karachi before leaving for
home on December 26. 
</P>
</TEXT>
