<DOCNO> XIE19971222.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Economy to Grow Moderately in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine economy,
battered by the protracted region-wide currency crisis, is
expected to grow by a moderate 4.5 percent in 1998 as measured by
gross national product (GNP), Socio-economic Planning Secretary
Cielito Habito said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The country's gross domestic product (GDP) is projected to grow
by 4 percent, the highest among Southeast Asian nations, Habito
said in a year-end report on the country's economic performance in
1997 and prospects for 1998.
</P>
<P>
The country's GNP grew by 6 percent during the first three
quarters this year, which Habito said was "respectable" compared
with its Southeast Asian neighbors.
</P>
<P>
"On the whole, while the Philippine economy has slowed down,
its performance remains respectable in comparison with our
neighbors," Habito said.
</P>
<P>
Habito attributed the still-steady economic growth to "strong
macroeconomic fundamentals and decisive policy responses made even
before the crisis unfolded."
</P>
<P>
The Philippine government scaled down its GNP growth target for
1997 from 7 percent to 5.5 percent due to the currency crisis
which struck Southeast Asia in July 1997 and then spread to other
parts of Asia. The country registered a 7.1 percent GNP growth
rate in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine peso has lost more than 50 percent of its value
against the U.S. dollar since July 11 when the Central Bank
decided to float the exchange rate.
</P>
<P>
According to Habito, the Philippine economy will face seven
major challenges in 1998, including a depressed regional economy,
lower capital flows to Asia and expected slowdown in U.S. and
Japanese economies.
</P>
<P>
The El Nino weather phenomenon, which has brought a severe
drought to the country since last month, will also pose a
challenge to the economy by severely affecting the agriculture
sector.
</P>
<P>
Other challenges are uncertainty over the country's May 1998
presidential election, continuing high interest rates and minimum
wage adjustments as a result of the peso devaluation.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, Habito said outlook remains bright for the
economy in 1998 as the implementation of programs reached
separately between the International Monetary Fund and Thailand,
Indonesia and South Korea is expected to stabilize regional
currencies.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the government had mapped out a contingency plan to
mitigate the adverse effects of El Nino, such as early importation
of rice to prevent a rice shortage next year.
</P>
<P>
The government will also continue to implement a six-point
action agenda to counter the currency crisis, including reducing
current account deficit, close monitoring of corporate and banking
sectors and continued implementation of economic reforms, Habito
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971222.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
