<HEADLINE> 1998 to See S. African Economy Up, Employment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 22 (Xinhua) -- South Africa will have
its economy grown slightly and inflation dropped next year, while
the living standards will be lower, the currency Rand depreciated
and unemployment increased, according to a latest public survey.
</P>
<P>
The survey, conducted by the South African Institute of Race
Relations, showed that the overall economy will probably grow by
three percent next year and this will get better at least until
the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
Private consumption expenditure will also grow by about three
percent, real gross domestic fixed investment will rise,
inflation is expected to drop from nine to 7.5 percent next year,
total budget expenditure is expected to grow by about 2.75
percent and the state's debt costs will fall.
</P>
<P>
The average effective exchange rate will drop by four percent
a year over the next few years, producer price inflation will
increase between five and 6.7 percent, and living standards will
fall slowly but steadily for some years, the survey said.
</P>
<P>
On employment issues, the survey said that unemployment was
probably increasing at an average of two percent a year, but the
1997 Medium Term Budget Policy Statement predicts it will grow
quickly over the next year by eight percent.
</P>
<P>
Most of the jobless are expected to be young and female
people, the survey said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
