<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africans Win World Cross Challenge in Brussels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Gete Wami of Ethiopia and
James Moiben of Kenya won the women's and men's races respectively
at Sunday's IAAF World Cross Challenge event.
</P>
<P>
Wami clocked 20 minutes 45 seconds in a 4-lap, 6,000-meter race
while Paula Radcliff of Britain finished three seconds behind at
second place, followed by Kutre Dulecha also from Ethiopia at
21:06.
</P>
<P>
Wami, third at the world cross-country championship race, led
in the second lap but was overtaken in the ensuing lap by Radcliff
who finished runner-up at the worlds.
</P>
<P>
World champion Derartu Tulu of Ethiopia did not participate in
Sunday's race due to an injury.
</P>
<P>
Wami said after the race that it was a very hard one though
there was not too much mud.
</P>
<P>
A continuous drizzle throughout the day muddied the course of
the cross-country race.
</P>
<P>
It was the fourth race the Ethiopian woman entered this year.
She won another race earlier in Spain and finished second in the
two others.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyans proved their depth in the cross-country event as
Moiben, who led for more than half the 7-lap, 10,500-meter race,
set the pace for a Kenyan one-two-three finish.
</P>
<P>
Moiben's winning time was 33 minutes 7 seconds, followed by
Thomas Nyariki and Paul Kosgei both at 33:12.
</P>
<P>
The men's race did not attract as strong a field as the women's
in this opening leg of the 11-leg IAAF World Cross Challenge event
that ends at the world cross-country championship slated for next
March in Morocco.
</P>
<P>
The top 20 finishers of the World Cross Challenge events are
awarded points that accumulate toward a final standing. The
winner is awarded 25 points while the runner-up 22 points and the
third-place finisher 19 points.
</P>
<P>
The others from the fourth place onward are awarded from 17
points down to one point. 
</P>
</TEXT>
