<DOCNO> XIE19971222.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Republicans, 60 Pct of Elected Delegates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Forty-six of the 76 elected
delegates at next year's Constitutional Convention support a
republic, with the Australian Republican Movement (ARM) making up
the largest single bloc with 27 delegates, the Australian
Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
Twenty-seven of the delegates support the monarchy, while three
delegates have not declared their position on the issue.
</P>
<P>
The final count Monday by the Australian Electoral Commission
for the convention scheduled for next February showed monarchists
outnumbered republicans only on Tasmania island and drew in South
Australia state.
</P>
<P>
Republicans swept the board in the two regions of Canberra and
the Northern Territory, won eight of the 13 positions in
Queensland state, nine of the 16 in Victoria state, with one
non-aligned, and 13 of the 20 in New South Wales state, with one
non-aligned.
</P>
<P>
ARM Chairman Malcolm Turnbull said the election showed that a
republic was the people's choice.
</P>
<P>
"It's a very good result," Turnbull told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"Obviously we are very comforted by the fact that the
Australian Republic Movement will be overwhelmingly the largest
group at the convention, with 27 out of the 76 delegates," he
declared.
</P>
<P>
ARM was followed by No Republic - Australians for a
Constitutional Monarchy with 19 delegates.
</P>
<P>
There is a two-to-one dominance in the electorate for an
Australian as head of state.
</P>
<P>
The 76 delegates are expected to make a decision at next
February's convention on whether Australia will become a republic.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
