<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Ends Stronger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar closed
higher Monday against its U.S. counterpart, as the crisis of
confidence in Asia continued.
</P>
<P>
It closed at 65.38 U.S. cents, up from 65.08 at the end of the
previous local session.
</P>
<P>
Traders said a U.S. buyer had been lodged at the 65.05 U.S.
cent region for most of the day, and this had helped put a floor
under the unit on the downside.
</P>
<P>
The bad news out of Asia continued Monday with Moody's
Investors Service announcing that it had downgraded the foreign
currency credit ratings of Indonesia, Malaysia, South Korea and
Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Moody said also that weakness in the Japanese economy and
banking system added a "further, negative backdrop to the
prospects for the region."
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar was at 84.91 Japanese yen, from 83.04
previously, and at 1.1660 German marks, from 1.1521. 
</P>
