<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 45 Percent Australians Considered Overweight: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 22 (Xinhua) -- About 45 percent of the
Australian men and 29 percent of the women are considered
overweight, as they eat more, drink more, the Australian Bureau of
Statistics said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The bureau released a national nutrition survey of nearly
14,000 people, providing a comprehensive snapshot of people's
eating habits and weight.
</P>
<P>
A further 18 percent of both men and women were classified as
obese.
</P>
<P>
The proportion of overweight or obese people increased with age
and peaked at 50-54 years for men and 60-64 years for women.
</P>
<P>
And after the age of 45, only around a quarter of men and 35
percent of women were within an acceptable weight range.
</P>
<P>
On average, Australian men consumed more food and beverages
than women in all age groups.
</P>
<P>
Men aged 19-24 ate the most, while women aged between 25 and 44
had the highest food intake.
</P>
<P>
The survey found that around 30 percent of adults believe they
should eat more fruit and vegetables, while around one quarter
thought they should eat less foods high in fat.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
