<DOCNO> XIE19971222.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Stock Market Closes Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The Australian stock market
closed lower Monday, overshadowed by Wall Street's negative
influences and falling Tokyo and Hong Kong markets.
</P>
<P>
Henderson Charlton Jones broker Philip Toop said poor overseas
trading over the past few days had impacted heavily on the local
bourse.
</P>
<P>
"It had a negative influence throughout the day," Toop said.
</P>
<P>
A buoyant gold sector helped to hold the all ordinaries, which
finished down 24.7 points at 2503.4, after Homestake Mining Co.
announced it would acquire Plutonic Resources in a deal it said
would create the third largest North American-based gold producer.
</P>
<P>
"The gold sector was stronger ... there could be some
speculation of more takeovers in that sector (firming up stocks),"
Toop said.
</P>
<P>
Gold shares defied the general weakness and the index was up
23.2 points at 945.8. Sydney trading in gold bullion closed at
289.80 U.S. dollars an ounce, up 1.55 U.S. dollars on Friday's
close of 288.25 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Shares in Plutonic were 16 Australian cents stronger at 2.80
Australian dollars each before a trading halt was placed on its
securities ahead of Homestake takeover announcement Monday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Homestake will acquire Plutonic for 640 million U.S. dollars in
stock, with the U.S.-owned company expecting to issue about 64.3
million shares to acquire Plutonic, or 0.34 of a Homestake common
share for each Plutonic ordinary share.
</P>
<P>
The all resources index finished down 5.6 points at 1080.9
while the all industrial index dropped 47.9 points to 4287.6.
</P>
<P>
Amongst the resource companies, BHP ended up 7.9 cents at 13.74
Australian dollars, having recovered from an earlier low of 13.483
Australian dollars. Global miner Rio Tinto lost 20.6 cents to
16.80 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The banking index fell 43.9 points to 5263.4 with ANZ bank
slipping 25 cents to 9.50 Australian dollars, National Australia
Bank declining 13 cents to 20.22 Australian dollars and
Commonwealth down six cents to 17.27 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Westpac edged down 0.1 cents to 9.399 Australian dollars, St.
George Bank shed 12 cents to 8.58 Australian dollars and Macquarie
Bank lost two cents to 11.30 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 241.09 million shares worth 462.72
million U.S. dollars, with falls of 565 outnumbering rises of 392.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
