<HEADLINE> Share Prices Decline Sharply on Singapore Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Share prices declined
sharply on the Singapore market on lingering negative regional
sentiment, as the benchmark Straits Times Industrials Index lost
30.96 points to close at 1541.65, down by two percent, Monday.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said that last Friday's crash of a Boeing plane of
SilkAir, a subsidiary of the national carrier Singapore Airlines
(SIA), injected some pessimism into the market.
</P>
<P>
However, they noted that Singapore stocks did not bear as much
losses as some of the other stock markets in the region.
</P>
<P>
The market could be trying to feel the bottom right now, one
broker said.
</P>
<P>
Total market volume stood at 133.11 million units, worth 307.82
million Singapore dollars (about 183.23 million U.S. dollars).
Declines overwhelmed advances by 278 to 53, while 274 other
counter remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Uraco was the most actively traded counter as it registered a
turnover of 15.57 million units. It was followed by the Singapore
Telecom which had 6.63 million shares traded. DBS (Development
Bank of Singapore) Land was next with 5.42 million shares changed
hands.
</P>
<P>
IPCO led the gainers of the day as it rose by 40 cents to
finish at 2.85 U.S. dollars. TLB Land increased by 35 cents to end
at 1.55 Singapore dollars, while JMH (Jardine Matheson Holdings)
400 picked up 22 cents to close at 4.62 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the downside, the Singapore Press Holdings (SPH) Foreign and
Sea View shared the top spot on the losers' list as each of them
declined by 70 cents to end at 21.9 and 6.5 Singapore dollars
respectively. City Development fell by 45 cents to close at 7.75
Singapore dollars, and the Singapore Airlines (SIA) lost 40 cents
to finish at 7.4 Singapore dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
