<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Food Distribution Sites Opened in California </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, December 21 (Xinhua) -- A local hunger relief
organization in California opened more food pantry distribution
sites to meet the needs of thousands of Californians who worry
about their next meal.
</P>
<P>
In San Francisco alone, more than 90,000 people, including
20,000 infants, children and adolescents, live at or below the
poverty line. That means one in 10 adults and one in five children
regularly go hungary, said a report by the local Food Bank.
</P>
<P>
While the federal government's poverty line for a family of
three is 13,500 U.S. dollars, a family of three with one wage
earner and two children needs an income of 36,000 dollars to live
a decent life in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
"Yet most households are making half of that or less," Paul
Ash, executive director of the San Francisco Food Bank, a local
hunger relief organization, told a local newspaper.
</P>
<P>
After paying for housing, utilities and transportation, many
families have little money left for food, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Food Bank is expected to increase annual distribution by
more than 50 percent, from 7.5 million pounds last year to more
than 11 million pounds this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971222.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commissioner's Office Supports HKSAR in Handling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Coordination and support have also been provided to the HKSAR
government in receiving foreign heads of state and in arranging
overseas visits for HKSAR officials.
</P>
<P>
All the work the commissioner office has done is conducive to
maintaining Hong Kong's position as an international financial,
trade, shipping, tourism and information center, enhancing its
status in the world and developing its relations with foreign
countries, Ma said.
</P>
<P>
Over the past half year, he pointed out, under the specific
instructions of the Chinese Foreign Ministry and in close
coordination with Chinese embassies and consulates in foreign
countries, the office of the commissioner has worked closely with
the HKSAR government departments in handling seven major
emergencies which jeopardized Hong Kong residents' interests and
lives.
</P>
<P>
These emergencies included an air crash in Phnom Penh, the
capsizing of a Philippine cruise with Hong Kong residents aboard,
the detention of Hong Kong fishing boats by the Philippines and
Japan and protection of Hong Kong people caught in military
conflicts in Phnom Penh.
</P>
<P>
Besides, he said, his office has also handled more than 90
other consular protection cases.
</P>
<P>
In handling these cases, the commissioner's office timely
provided the HKSAR government with information about Hong Kong
people in distress overseas from Chinese embassies and consulates
in those countries and speedily forwarded the requests of their
relatives in Hong Kong to the Chinese embassies and consulates as
well as to those distressed, he said.
</P>
<P>
Ma stressed that it is an important component part of his work
to protect the legitimate rights and interests of Hong Kong people
residing abroad.
</P>
<P>
"Our practice is to cooperate closely with Chinese embassies
and consulates in foreign countries and with the HKSAR government
and do our work with a strong sense of responsibility, a positive
attitude and high efficiency," he said.
</P>
<P>
Ma said his office will further enhance its contacts and
relations with various sectors and improve both the efficiency and
quality of consular services and protection so as to better
safeguard the legitimate rights and interests of the Hong Kong
people overseas.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
