<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WFP Project Produces Results in SW China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, December 22 (Xinhua) -- A World Food Program aid
program has achieved notable results in the Qujing area in
southwest China's Yunnan Province.
</P>
<P>
The WFP granted 82,710 tons of wheat to Qujing in 1992, with the
Yunnan Provincial government providing an aid package valued at
3.29 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Farmers receive a share of wheat in return for growing trees,
building dams, undertaking projects to block drifting sand,
transforming mountain slopes into terraced farmland and attending
part-time schools.
</P>
<P>
Some one third of the farmland in the project area, which
previously suffered from water and soil erosion, has access to
irrigation and its grain output has jumped 52 percent this year on
the 1992 level.
</P>
<P>
The project has also enabled 17,000 illiterates in the project
area to read and write.  
</P>
</TEXT>
