<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Decision to Submit HK Human Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 22 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese official has
described China's decision to provide relevant U.N. departments
with information about the implementation of two international
covenants on human rights in Hong Kong as a testimony to the
Chinese government's determination to fully implement the "one
country, two systems" policy.
</P>
<P>
The decision is of great significance to Hong Kong's long-term
prosperity and stability, Ma Yuzhen, commissioner of the Chinese
Foreign Ministry in the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
(HKSAR), said in an exclusive interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government announced on November 22 its decision to
provide to the United Nations information about the implementation
in the HKSAR of the relevant provisions of the International
Covenant on Civil and Political Rights and the International
Covenant on Economic, Social and Cultural Rights.
</P>
<P>
Ma said that in accordance with related provisions of the
Sino-British Joint Declaration on the Question of Hong Kong and
the Basic Law and in consideration of the fact that China is not
yet a party to the two covenants, the Chinese government will, on
the analogy of the relevant provisions of the two covenants, ask
China's Permanent Mission to the United Nations to hand to the
U.N. secretary-general a report on the implementation of the
relevant provisions of the two covenants in the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
If the report is to be deliberated upon by covenant
institutions, he said, the Chinese government will notify the
HKSAR of this and ask it to send representatives to answer
questions regarding the report.
</P>
<P>
The commissioner said the report on the implementation of the
relevant provisions of the two covenants will be written by the
HKSAR government and sent by the Office of the Commissioner of the
Chinese Foreign Ministry in the HKSAR to China's Permanent U.N.
Mission to pass it on to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
He noted that On December 4, Ambassador Qin Huasun, China's
permanent representative to the United Nations, formally presented
a note on the arrangement to the U.N. secretary-general and
requested the latter to put the note on record and at the same
time inform the covenant institutions and other parties to the
covenants.
</P>
<P>
"Such an arrangement fully shows the Chinese government's
resolve to implement the policy of 'one country, two systems' and
can help the international community understand better the human
rights situation in the HKSAR," he said.
</P>
<P>
It is of great significance to boosting the confidence of the
Hong Kong people and promoting the growth of economy and other
undertakings and maintaining long-term prosperity and stability in
the HKSAR, he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
