<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading French newspapers today:
</P>
<P>
Liberation:
</P>
<P>
-- French Prime Minister announced on Sunday in Bamako, Mali,
that France would not ornigaze massive expulsions of illegal
immigrants any more. Speaking in front of 146 parliament deputies of
Mali, Jospin also said that it is necessary to control the influx of
immigrants, because of the public opinion in France and because the
extreme-right National Front is taking advantage of the problem.
</P>
<P>
-- The Labor Party of Britain has decided to ``moralize'' the
arms sale of Europe and the French Socialist Party has received an
final version of ``code of good conduct'' from British Foreign
Secretary Robin Cook, who asked France to respond to the proposal as
soon as possible. The project is among the priorities of Britain
after it takes over the presidency of the European Union on January
1, 1998.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- The death of two youths, killed separately on Wednesday and
Thursday in Fontainbleau and Lyon by police, provoked riots last
weekend in the suburbs of the two cities. The city of Duchere in
Lyon, where a 24-year-old youth Fabrice Fernandez was killed, today
will observe a day of silence with all markets closed. The Interior
Minister Jean-Pierre Chevenemnent has denounced ``an unacceptable
slip-up'' by police in the two deaths, while the trade unions of
police have disowned their colleague in Lyon, who has been detained
for ``voluntary homicide.''
</P>
<P>
-- Ending a six-day trip to Africa, Prime Minister Lionel Jospin
affirmed on Sunday in Bamako, Mali, that France will put an end to
the prractice of massively expelling illegal immigrants on chartered
planes, and will instead repatriate them in a humane way. 
</P>
