<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Continue to Plunge in Tokyo for Fear of Credit Risks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Tokyo stock prices continued to
plunge Monday with the key Nikkei index ending below the 15,000
line for the first time since July 1995 for greater fear of credit
risks amid the sluggish economy.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei average of 225 selected issues on the First Section
of the Tokyo Stock Exchange finished at 14,799.40, down 515.49
points or 3.37 percent from last Friday's close.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
issues on the First Section, declined 37.38 points, or 3.2 percent
to 1,130.00.
</P>
<P>
Volume on the First Section came to an estimated 660 million
shares, down from Friday's 711.83 million shares.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei index ended well below the previous closing low for
the year of 15,082.52, marked November 14.
</P>
<P>
Traders said the index is likely to test 14,485.41, set on July
3, 1995, the lowest closing price since the burst of the
asset-inflated bubble economy in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
Concerns over credit risk, originally concentrated in the
financial sector, have now spread to nonfinancial companies,
traders said.
</P>
<P>
Of the 1,327 issues listed on the First Section, losers
outweighed gainers 1,026 to 169 with 92 issues unchanged.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the sharp fall of share prices, Osama Watanabe,
vice minister of Japan's Ministry of International Trade and
Industry, said the recent price falls have been led by speculative
trading. He called on market players to be prudent.
</P>
<P>
The Tokyo market will be closed Tuesday for a national holiday.
</P>
</TEXT>
