<HEADLINE> Sino-Ukrainian Enterprises to Expand Links </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government will
encourage Chinese enterprises to invest in the Ukraine, according
to Minister of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation Wu Yi.
</P>
<P>
Wu made the remarks at a forum attended by visiting Ukrainian
Prime Minister Valery Pustovoitenko and some 80 representatives
from 18 Chinese and 13 Ukrainian companies.
</P>
<P>
The forum was held at the Ministry of Foreign Trade and
Economic Cooperation (MOFTEC).
</P>
<P>
Wu said that China has always attached great importance to
developing friendly cooperative relations with the Ukraine. She
noted that active trade and economic cooperation is an important
component of bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
She said that the Ukraine is an important country in Europe and
one of China's most important trade partners in the Commonwealth
of Independent States (CIS). She said the highly complementary
economies of the two nations provide a rare opportunity for
the expansion of bilateral economic and trade cooperation.
</P>
<P>
She expressed the hope that Pustovoitenko's visit and the forum
will enable entrepreneurs from the two countries to further
enhance mutual understanding, trust and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
She proposed that Ukrainian enterprises hold an investment
fair in China at an appropriate time in the future.
</P>
<P>
Pustovoitenko said the Ukraine regards China as a "strategic
partner in foreign economic and trade cooperation." He noted that
the bilateral trade volume exceeded one billion US dollars in
1997, and stressed that the vast potential for economic and trade
cooperation between the two countries has not as yet been fully
tapped.
</P>
<P>
He said the Ukrainian government will continue to extend a
great effort to develop mutually beneficial economic and trade
cooperation with countries in the Asia-Pacific Region, especially
China.
</P>
<P>
Pustovoitenko said the Ukraine plans to develop trade links
with the region into a new pillar of economic growth.
</P>
<P>
He expressed hope that the two countries will continue to
expand cooperation in the sectors such as power generation,
metallurgy, machine-building, chemicals, mining, military
technology, aviation and shipbuilding.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed the hope that two-way trade will grow to
between 2-3 billion US dollars by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Wu and Pustovoitenko also answered questions from participating
entrepreneurs.  
</P>
</TEXT>
