<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No More Fertilizer Loans for Zambian Farmers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government has
said that it will not give out fertilizer loans to farmers for
the 1997-98 season as they have failed to pay back the loans
disbursed during the previous season.
</P>
<P>
Zambia Daily Mail today quoted Agriculture, Food and Fisheries
Minister Edith Nawakwi as saying here Sunday that the farmers
should instead resort to crops that don't require fertilizer to
give positive yields.
</P>
<P>
Nawakwi said it doesn't make sense for the government to
continue handing out loans if farmers don't repay.
</P>
<P>
It is said that farmers have been unable to pay back loans
amounting to over 15 billion Kwacha (about 11 million U.S.
Dollars) during the previous season.
</P>
<P>
She said farmers should buy fertilizer from the private sector
and from the European Union which has stocks left over from last
season's consignment.
</P>
<P>
She told the farmers to plant other food crops that don't
require fertilizer such as soya beans, sunflower, beans, cassava
and groundnuts.
</P>
<P>
"In fact these crops enhance household food security, they
will help people who are now crying for food," she said.
</P>
<P>
She told people not to sell their maize because hunger was
likely in December.
</P>
<P>
The minister announced that farmers who want seeds of soya and
sunflower should approach the program against malnutrition where
the commodity could be provided.
</P>
<P>
The government has been given money by the World Bank to
purchase the seeds for farmers under the poverty alleviation
program.
</P>
<P>
"The World Bank has given us money enough to buy seed for
drought resistant crops and we are offering that," Nawakwi said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
