<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Troubled Tanzanian Printer Privatized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania's ailing
printing giant, Printpak Tanzania Limited, will be privatized by
sale to a Dar es Salaam bidder.
</P>
<P>
The privatization agency last week awarded the bid to Infotech
Investment Group, a company which sells computers. The other
bidders were Tanzania Printing Services and Printpak staff and
management.
</P>
<P>
Details of the sale agreement have not been concluded and the
fate of its 286 work force is yet to be determined, East African
said today.
</P>
<P>
The draft agreement says Infotech Investment Group will
acquire 75 percent of Printpak shares, and the rest will be held
in trust by the government for eventual floatation to the public
when the Dar es Salaam Stock Exchange takes off.
</P>
<P>
Formed in 1966, Printpak has a capacity of printing up to 75
million copies of book and 40 million copies of newspapers and
magazines annually.
</P>
<P>
It has an ink factory with the capacity to produce 120 tons of
oil-based printing inks and 100 tons of flexo ink.
</P>
<P>
However, it has been undergoing severe financial problems
linked to the fact that its main client, the state-owned
publishers of Daily News and Sunday News, has a debt of one
billion shillings (about 1.5 million U.S. Dollars) and
competition from at least 30 new licensed printers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971222.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FM Commissioner Pledges to Abide by "One Country, Two Systems" Concept </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The commissioner of the
Chinese Foreign Ministry in the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (SAR) has pledged to fully implement the "one country, two
systems" concept and said his office and the HKSAR government are
not subordinate to each other.
</P>
<P>
Ma Yuzhen stressed in a recent exclusive interview with Xinhua
that there exists a relationship of mutual respect, mutual trust,
mutual support and close cooperation between the office of the
commissioner and the HKSAR government.
</P>
<P>
"In its work, the office will strictly abide by the provisions
of the Basic Law of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region of
the People's Republic of China," Ma said.
</P>
<P>
Summing up his office's work since its establishment after Hong
Kong's return to China on July 1, Ma noted that the best way to
implement the "one country, two systems" principle is to act
strictly in accordance with the Basic Law, which stipulates that
the Central People's Government shall be responsible for the
foreign affairs relating to the HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the central government has authorized the
HKSAR to conduct relevant external affairs on its own in
accordance with the Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Chapter VII of the Basic Law stipulates in detail
how the HKSAR should deal with its external affairs, Ma said,
adding that this means that the office of the commissioner does
not handle all the external affairs affecting the HKSAR, Ma said.
</P>
<P>
"We should give the HKSAR government a free hand in dealing
with the affairs within the authorization of the Basic Law and we
should fully trust the HKSAR government and bring its initiative
into full play."
</P>
<P>
The commissioner stressed that to implement the policy of
"one country, two systems," his office must follow the practice
of seeking truth from facts and proceeding from actual conditions.
</P>
<P>
The Basic Law states that representatives of the HKSAR may, as
members of Chinese delegations, participate in international
organizations or conferences in appropriate fields limited to
states and affecting the region, or may attend in such other
capacity as may be permitted by the Central People's Government
and the international organization or conference concerned, and
may express their views, using the name "Hong Kong, China."
</P>
<P>
After Hong Kong's return to China, there are still civil
servants of foreign nationalities working in the HKSAR government
and some of them are in important positions, Ma said.
</P>
<P>
"In light of the actual situation, we agreed to let them
participate in the World Conference on Intellectual Property
Rights, the International Conference on Civil Aviation and the
International Conference on Postal Service as members of the
Chinese government delegations and sit in the first rows together
with senior members of our government delegations."
</P>
<P>
Permitting foreign nationals to take part in international
conferences as members of a government delegation is something not
only unprecedented in the diplomatic history of New China but also
rare in the history of international diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
The foreign civil servants concerned were deeply moved and
greatly encouraged by such a practice, which has been highly
commended by the international community, Ma said.
</P>
<P>
"To implement the policy of 'one country, two systems'," he
said, "we must also abandon old ideas and develop new thinking and
 new methods to address the problems cropping up in the new
situation."
</P>
<P>
He cited as an example the Chinese government's decision to
provide the United Nations with information about the
implementation in the HKSAR of the relevant provisions of the
International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights and the
International Covenant on Economic, Social and Cultural Rights.
</P>
<P>
Ma pointed out that under the two covenants, only the parties
to the covenants have the obligation to report on the
implementation and China is not yet a party.
</P>
<P>
However, to reflect the principle of "one country, two systems"
and enhance the confidence of the Hong Kong people and by taking
the needs of the HKSAR into consideration, the central government
handled this issue in a flexible manner, Ma said.
</P>
<P>
"To implement the principle of 'one country, two systems', we
must establish good relations with the government of the HKSAR and
should respect, support and trust the HKSAR in our work," the
commissioner said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the HKSAR is a local administrative region of
the People's Republic of China, which enjoys a high degree of
autonomy and is directly under the jurisdiction of the Central
People's Government.
</P>
<P>
The chief executive of the HKSAR is accountable to the Central
People's Government and to the HKSAR while the office of the
commissioner is an office established by the Chinese Foreign
Ministry in the HKSAR to deal with foreign affairs and it is
answerable to the Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the two are not subordinate to each other and their
relationship is one of mutual respect, mutual trust, mutual
support and close cooperation, Ma said.
</P>
<P>
For instance, it is entirely up to the HKSAR government to
decide on its senior officials' overseas visits, including where
and when to go, whom to meet and what to discuss.
</P>
<P>
When HKSAR Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa visits foreign
countries, China's ambassadors to these countries greet and see
him off at airports and hold receptions in his honor, but they do
not participate in his talks with local hosts or other activities.
</P>
<P>
It is also up to the HKSAR government to decide whether and how
to receive foreign heads of state or government officials who wish
to visit Hong Kong. Officials of the commissioner's office do not
take part in the talks between HKSAR officials and visiting
foreign heads of state or government officials.
</P>
<P>
Officials of the HKSAR government said that thanks to the
support and trust of the Central People's Government, they enjoyed
high-level treatment in international affairs.
</P>
<P>
Ma, a career diplomat for decades, noted that the principle of
"one country, two systems" is new and there is no precedent for
his office to follow in its work.
</P>
<P>
"This requires us to be both prudent and open-minded and dare
to blaze a new trail," he said.
</P>
<P>
In the future, the office of the commissioner will continue to
abide by the provisions of the Basic Law and make efforts to
implement in earnest the principle of "one country, two systems,"
Ma emphasized.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
