<HEADLINE> Poultry Disease Troubles S. African Ostrich </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 22 (Xinhua) -- South Africa, a major
supplier of ostrich meat to the European Union (EU), would have
to stop exporting the meat because of poultry disease, local
daily the Star reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Standing Veterinary Committee of the European Commission
and a South African delegation have decided to give the latter's
ostrich industry another chance to clean up Newcastle disease and
meet the new European regulations and standards.
</P>
<P>
In July, the European Commission published a list of countries
outside the EU which would be allowed to export ostrich meat to
EU countries from next month, and left out South Africa and
countries within the Southern African Development Community
(SADC) region.
</P>
<P>
South Africa vehemently objected to the EU and said six
abattoirs were already approved for export to the EU and their
names supplied to the European Commission last year, Gideon
Bruchkner, director of public veterinary health, was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Currently, more than 80 percent of all ostrich meat exported
to the EU originated from South Africa, according to South
Africa's Department of Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Bruckner said that the European Commission's decision was a
temporary reprieve for South Africa and that if major moves to
eradicate the disease in the next six months were unsuccessful,
the EU would stop importing South African ostrich meat.
</P>
<P>
"The presence of Newcastle disease in poultry and ostriches in
South Africa is still a major stumbling block in convincing the
European Commission that the export of poultry meat poses no risk
of transmitting disease to European countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
Newcastle disease was a viral infection, affecting poultry
throughout South Africa, and had been in the country for many
years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
