<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commissioner's Office in HKSAR Runs Smoothly: Ma (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The commissioner of the
Chinese Foreign Ministry in the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (HKSAR) has expressed satisfaction with his office's work,
saying the office has been operating smoothly with its work on the
right track.
</P>
<P>
In a recent interview with Xinhua, Ma Yuzhen said that over the
past half year, the commissioner's office has briefed the consular
corps in Hong Kong and the local media on its functions and duties
and established a working relationship with them.
</P>
<P>
It has also set up an effective mechanism of cooperation with
the HKSAR government, enjoyed pleasant cooperation with both Chief
Executive Tung Chee Hwa and the HKSAR government and won the
approval and support of the Hong Kong people.
</P>
<P>
"I think it is appropriate to say that we have a fairly good
start in our work," Ma said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the commissioner's office is a body dealing with
the foreign affairs relating to the HKSAR, which is part of the
Central People's Government's responsibility, and it also serves
as a communication channel between the central government and the
HKSAR in the field of foreign affairs.
</P>
<P>
Ma added that other major tasks of his office are to assist the
HKSAR in handling on its own the external affairs within
authorization and discharge other duties entrusted by the Central
People's Government and the Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
He identified his office's specific areas of work as conducting
policy research, helping the HKSAR government deal with matters
relating to consular affairs, handling or assisting the HKSAR
government in solving any problems Hong Kong may have with
international organizations, international conferences and
international treaties and laws, and dealing with any other
matters related to foreign affairs.
</P>
<P>
The commissioner said his office has been doing its work
according to the foreign policies of the central government, the
principle of "one country, two systems" and the provisions of the
Basic Law.
</P>
<P>
The objective is to safeguard state sovereignty and national
interests, protect Hong Kong compatriots' legitimate rights and
interests and promote long-term prosperity and stability in Hong
Kong.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971222.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commissioner's Office in HKSAR Runs Smoothly: Ma (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The office's guidelines are to support, respect and trust the
HKSAR government and cooperate with it closely, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Our code of work is to do whatever is conducive to
implementing the 'one country, two systems' concept and
safeguarding state sovereignty, promoting Hong Kong's prosperity
and stability, maintaining Hong Kong's position as an
international shipping, financial, trade, tourism and information
center and its status as a free port and bolstering understanding,
trust and relationship between the central government and the
HKSAR government."
</P>
<P>
Reviewing the office's operations and main achievements over
the past half year, Ma said that under the leadership of the
Foreign Ministry, his office has given assistance to
representatives of the HKSAR government in attending the
conferences of nearly 30 international organizations including the
World Intellectual Property Organization and the Universal Postal
Union as members of Chinese delegations.
</P>
<P>
The office of the commissioner has also assisted the HKSAR in
attending some international conferences under the name "Hong
Kong, China."
</P>
<P>
It has passed on to the HKSAR 15 instruments from the central
government authorizing the HKSAR to negotiate with more than 30
countries over 40 bilateral agreements covering the six areas of
air transit, investment protection, surrender of fugitive
offenders, transfer of sentenced persons, juridical assistance to
criminal matters and civil aviation, he said.
</P>
<P>
The commissioner's office has also processed large numbers of
Chinese travel documents and granted visas to foreigners for
travel from Hong Kong to China's mainland.
</P>
<P>
The commissioner's office also assisted in dealing with seven
major emergencies which put the life and property of Hong Kong
compatriots in jeopardy, handled more than 90 consular protection
cases related to Hong Kong, and dozens of applications from
foreign consulates for foreign warships to make port calls or
their government aircraft for fly-over and stopover in Hong Kong,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Ma attributed the progress of his office's work to the earnest
implementation of the Basic Law and strict adherence to the
instructions of the Central People's Government and the Foreign
Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The progress is also inseparable from the active support and
cooperation of the HKSAR government and Hong Kong people from all
walks of life, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
