<HEADLINE> Floods Strand Relief Food to N. Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Eleven lorries,
carrying 36 tons of relief food to Musoma in Tanzania's northern
region of Mara, have been stranded after heavy rains swept
several bridges.
</P>
<P>
The lorries carrying relief food supplies donated by the World
Food Program (WFP) have been stranded for the past three days at
Magu in Mwanza region which neighbors Mara, "The Guardian" said
today.
</P>
<P>
The continuing heavy rains have also damaged 300 houses in
Magu district, making more than 2,000 people homeless.
</P>
<P>
The Magu District Commissioner, Reuben Ole Kunei, said Sunday
that the houses have been damaged in Kisamba, Kisesa, Magu, and
Lubuga wards.
</P>
<P>
He said that communication in the district had been disrupted
as a number of bridges have been washed away by floods making
roads impassable.
</P>
<P>
Ole Kunei also expressed fears that the four remaining bridges
might also be washed away if the rains continue.
</P>
<P>
He said the government has done everything possible to make sure
that all homeless people got medical assistance and basics.
</P>
<P>
Because of floods, prices of consumer items in Musoma town have
shot up by more than 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
Musoma town has been cut off from other areas after a bridge at
Rubana River was washed away by floods. The bridge connects Mara and
Mwanza regions, and Mara region with the Kenyan border. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
