<HEADLINE> Shanghai Protects Rare Plants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai has introduced 140
species of rare plants under state protection into the city from
other parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the Shanghai Botanical Garden (SBG) is home to the
largest number of "foreign plants" in China.
</P>
<P>
Introducing a variety of plants is an important aspect of
protection. Shanghai lacks indigenous plant resources, especially
rare species. However, the city's warm moist climate is highly
conducive to plant growth, according to experts.
</P>
<P>
The SBG has introduced more than 3,000 species of arbors and
bushes from other parts of the country and the world.
</P>
<P>
The Cathaya Argyrophylla, a rare and ancient tree regarded as
the "giant panda of plants", survived transplantation in Shanghai,
but has not grown well due to is heat resistance
characteristics. However, researchers are working diligently to
solve the problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
