<HEADLINE> WHO Coordinates Efforts to Combat Cholera in E. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The World Health Organization
(WHO) has organized an emergency meeting to coordinate efforts by
East African countries to combat an epidemic disease of cholera,
The East African reported today.
</P>
<P>
The weekly newspaper said that the WHO would increase
technical assistance to all cholera-endemic countries in the
fields of health education, training and the enhancement of
laboratory facilities.
</P>
<P>
It was resolved at the meeting held here last week that each
of the affected countries would form a task force for the
management and distribution of cholera treatment supplies.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that more than 2,500 people already died of
the disease this year in Kenya, Tanzania, Uganda, Somalia and
Djibouti and infection rates had risen during the past month.
</P>
<P>
Two months of heavy rain in the East African region have had
an adverse impact on the spread of the disease with cholera cases
tending to pick up as flood waters recede, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
At least 555 people were killed by the disease in kenya by the
end of last week out of 17,200 cases reported since june this
year while in mainland Tanzania about 1,700 died of the disease
out of 34,449 cases since last January.
</P>
<P>
In the worst-hit Kenya and Tanzania, the health authorities
have established cholera treating centers where those are
suffering from the disease are examined and treated free of
charge.
</P>
<P>
Maria Neira, co-ordinator of the global task force on cholera
control was quoted as saying that the movement of thousands of
refugees and other displaced people in the region and flood
waters were mainly attributed to the wide-spread of the disease
in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
