<HEADLINE> Guangzhou Levies Fees for Waste Water Treatment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Guangzhou, the provincial
capital of south China's Guangdong Province will begin to levy
fees for waste water treatment, beginning on January 1, next year.
</P>
<P>
Regulations on the collection of waste water treatment fees have
been worked out, Dai Zhiguo, vice-mayor of Guangzhou, was quoted by
the Guangzhou-based Yangcheng Evening News as saying.
</P>
<P>
All government departments, enterprises and residents in the
city are required to pay for the waste water treatment. The waste
water treatment fee is 0.2 yuan (8.2 yuan equal one US dollars)
per ton.
</P>
<P>
The Guangzhou city discharges about 2.6 million tons of
industrial or household waste water into the Zhujiang River each
day.
</P>
<P>
Dai said 11 waste water treatment plants will be built in the
city by the year 2010, with a total daily treating capacity of
over three million tons. Construction of them needs eight billion
yuan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
