<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Strengthens Research on Golden Monkeys </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Seven golden monkeys have been
bred in the Lanzhou Zoo in northwest China's Gansu Province over
the past five years.
</P>
<P>
The success in breeding the animal is regarded as a remarkable
achievement of the zoologists' research.
</P>
<P>
The population of the golden monkeys in the world is no more
than several thousands. China has three types of golden monkey,
classified according to their geographic locations. They inhabit
in mountainous areas, from 1,500 to 3,800 m above sea level in
Sichuan, Yunnan and Guizhou provinces in southwest China and in
Shaanxi and Gansu provinces in northwest China.
</P>
<P>
The lovely monkeys with beautiful golden hair are under
first-class state protection. Experts in the Northwest China
Teacher's College and Gansu Agricultural University have carried
out special researches on the golden monkey's habits,
characteristics, and environment.
</P>
<P>
Yu Shiyuan, a zoologist at Northwest China Teacher's College,
said their research showed that golden monkeys have well-developed
respiratory system.
</P>
<P>
Golden monkeys that are nimble and can run fast have more
survival chances, added Yu.
</P>
<P>
However, golden monkeys have a low reproduction rate. They mate
in late fall, and have a gestation period of six months, usually
giving birth to one offspring. They are sexually mature at four to
six years of age and have a life expectancy of 16 to 18 years.
</P>
<P>
Experts researches have greatly helped the breeding of golden
monkeys in the Lanzhou Zoo. Out of the 50 golden monkeys
artificially propagated in China, seven were born in the zoo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
