<HEADLINE> Xinjiang Protects Cultural Heritage of Folk Art </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Northwest China's Xinjiang
Uygur Autonomous Region has adopted effective measures to protect
the cultural heritage of folk art.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Ji, director of the Xinjiang Art Institute, noted that
Xinjiang has abundant historical relics, and is also famous for
its colorful traditional art forms dating back to the ancient
"Silk Road".
</P>
<P>
As part of an effort to save traditional art forms, local art
troupes have invited a number of folk artists to stage
performances of ethnic minority songs and dances in danger of
being lost, according to Zhou.
</P>
<P>
Since the early 1980s, local art departments have extended
great effort to compile and publish a series of collections
covering local opera, traditional music, ethnic minority musical
instruments, and folk songs and dances.
</P>
<P>
Researchers and artists in Xinjiang have formed a special
art troupe and research center to save and develop the famous
"Mukarm Songs", a traditional musical performance staged for the
family of the Uygur ruler in the 16th century, said Zhou.
</P>
<P>
All records and published works related to the music
have been compiled and performances of the "Mukarm Songs" have
been staged for audiences nationwide. 
</P>
</TEXT>
