<HEADLINE> Imported Medicine Challenges China's Pharmaceutical Industry (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Experts pointed out that reorienting new drug research from
simply imitation to invention is the key to extricating the
Chinese pharmaceutical industry from its current difficult
position.
</P>
<P>
The SPAC's Administrative Center for New Drug Research and
Development has allocated 50 million yuan (six million US dollars)
to support 382 research projects in the pharmaceutical
industry. Related efforts have already yielded the development of
over a dozen new drugs.
</P>
<P>
The goal of the country's pharmaceutical industry is to regain
some of its former market share by expanding the production scale
of new drugs, said Zheng.
</P>
<P>
The Zhonghui Pharmaceutical Co., a subsidiary of the China
Academy of Traditional Chinese Medicine and the largest company of
its kind in China, has completed a new plant with an annual
capacity to produce traditional Chinese medicine valued at five
billion yuan. The plant is located in Chengdu, capital of
southwest China's Sichuan Province.
</P>
<P>
The China Academy of Traditional Chinese Medicine will help
face the challenge from imported medicines by encouraging the
company's development of new products, including "Tangmaikang" for
treating diabetes and "Tongfengding" for gout.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that few new domestic drugs have reached an
appropriate production scale, and less than 3,000 professionals
are currently involved in new drug research.
</P>
<P>
As part of its efforts to ease the shortage of funds and
talented professionals in the new drug research sector, the
country welcomes foreign investors to establish joint ventures
engaged in processing, technical transfers, joint research and new
product development, according to a SPAC spokesman. 
</P>
</TEXT>
