<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Imported Medicine Challenges China's Pharmaceutical Industry (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 22 (Xinhua) -- China's pharmaceutical
industry should expand its production scale of new products in
order to compete with foreign counterparts, an official with the
State Pharmaceutical Administration of China (SPAC) stressed here
today.
</P>
<P>
Imported medicines and products manufactured by foreign-funded
enterprises currently occupy nearly 60 percent of the market in
some large Chinese cities due to the lack of an adequate
production scale for new domestic medicines, according to SPAC
Director Zheng Xiaoyu.
</P>
<P>
China, the world's second largest pharmaceutical producer, has
an annual capacity to produce 1,350 varieties of raw chemical
medicines and 4,000 kinds of Chinese herbal medicines, said Zheng.
</P>
<P>
With the exception of herbal medicines, more than 97 percent of
chemical drugs are imitations of foreign products. Up to now, no
Chinese chemical drug has been patented in a foreign country,
according to Zheng.
</P>
<P>
Experts note that herbal medicines manufactured in the Republic
of Korea and Japan also pose a major threat to Chinese herbal
medicines.
</P>
<P>
International sales of herbal medicines currently stand at 15
billion US dollars annually, with Chinese traditional medicines
accounting for a mere four percent of the total.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
