<HEADLINE> Chinese Develops Trans-Gene Anti-Pests Cotton Varieties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists have
successfully developed 11 trans-gene anti-pests cotton varieties
and three anti-pests crossbred varieties.
</P>
<P>
Field tests have indicated the trans-gene cotton varieties can
kill more than 80 percent of the cotton bollworms, pink bollworms
and leaf rollers. They can also inherit the anti-pests gene to
their later generations.
</P>
<P>
Experts here said the new cotton varieties are up to the world
level.
</P>
<P>
Being one of the major state science and technology projects,
the trans-gene cotton project was jointly launched by 18 research
units headed by Jiangsu Academy of Agricultural Science.
</P>
<P>
After years of experiments, Chinese scientists have
successfully introduce anti-pests gene into cotton varieties in
cotton-growing areas along the Yellow River and Yangtze River
basin areas.
</P>
<P>
Molecular tests showed that the anti-pests gene are expressed
and integrated in the new cotton varieties.
</P>
<P>
In the past three years, Chinese scientists made trial planting
of the trans-gene cotton varieties in 1,670 hectares of land in
East China's Jiangsu and Anhui provinces, and central China's
Henan province. The cotton yield witnessed an increase of at least
8 percent.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the usage of pesticide can be reduced by 50
percent, scientists said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
