<HEADLINE> India Urged to Temper CAC Move Due to Asian Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 22 (Xinhua) -- India should not rush in to
adopt capital account convertibility (CAC) of the rupee in view of
the currency and stock market crisis rocking the South-East Asian
countries, the paper Business Standard Monday quoted a noted
economist as saying.
</P>
<P>
The signing of the financial services pact under the aegis of
the World Trade Organization (WTO) would go a long way in building
up the Indian financial sector and would also have a ripple effect
on the other sectors, Jagdish Bhagwati said here.
</P>
<P>
The signing of the pact, however, does not mean that India
should go for convertibility of the rupee as the country's foreign
trade is not large enough to absorb the aftershocks of the
currency turmoil prevailing in other parts of the world, Bhagwati
said.
</P>
<P>
He urged the Indian government to do its homework to clearly
define and substantiate its stand on issues like labor and
environmental standards, anti-trust and competition policies.
</P>
<P>
For instance, he said, the government should spell out as to
what kind of labor and environmental standards it wants instead of
merely opposing the stand of western countries on the issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
