<HEADLINE> Thai Ministry to Launch Drive for Export Promotion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's Commerce Ministry
will launch nearly 390 activities at home and abroad next year to
promote exports of Thai goods in a bid to reduce the current
account deficit, the Nation newspaper reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Ninety-five of these activities, including trade fairs,
exhibitions and trade missions, will be held in Asia, which is
seen as the most important market for Thai exports.
</P>
<P>
Main promotion targets in Asia are the Association of Southeast
Asian Nations, China (including Taiwan) and Japan.
</P>
<P>
Sixty promotion activities have been planned for Europe, 56 for
the Americas, 18 for the Middle East, 16 for Australia and New
Zealand and three for Africa.
</P>
<P>
About 140 promotion events will be arranged within Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The weakening baht has made Thai exports cheaper and Thailand's
exports in the last three months (September to November) this year
were on the rise, following a drastic slowdown last year and the
first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
Among Thailand's main exports are computers and parts,
garments, rubber, rice and frozen and canned seafood.
</P>
<P>
Agricultural and marine products, which do not need much
imported content, are expected to have good export prospects.
</P>
