<DOCNO> XIE19971222.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Capital Expenditure Ratio Falls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The ratio of capital
expenditure to gross domestic product (GDP) has steadily declined
in India since 1991 to reach its lowest 3.6 percent in 1996-97,
Federation of Indian Chambers of Commerce and Industry (FICCI)
sources said Monday.
</P>
<P>
One of the major reasons for the current slowdown of the
economy is the cumulative impact of the declining trend of capital
expenditure and capital formation, FICCI said in an analysis on
"Capital Expenditure and Gross Capital Formation Since
Liberalization."
</P>
<P>
It described the declining ratio of capital expenditure to GDP
over the years as a matter of great concern after analyzing the
data on capital expenditure and gross capital formation during the
1990-91 to 1996-97.
</P>
<P>
According to FICCI, in 1990-91, the capital expenditure was 5.9
percent of the GDP and the corresponding gross capital formation
was 6.5 percent of the GDP.
</P>
<P>
In the year 1992-93, the capital expenditure ratio fell to 4.2
percent, pushing down the gross capital formation to 5.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
In the year 1993-94, capital expenditure remained at 4.2
percent whereas the gross capital formation showed a slight
increase to 5.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
In 1994-95, capital expenditure fell to 4.1 percent whereas the
gross capital formation marginally went up to 5.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
A drastic fall in capital expenditure took place in 1995-96
when it went down to 3.6 percent pulling down in its course the
rate of capital formation to 5.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
For the year 1996-97, capital expenditure fell further to 3.4
percent and gross capital formation to 4.9 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971222.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Privatization Law Announced in Romania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, December 21 (Xinhua) -- The Romanian government
announced Sunday that a law on privatization has been passed to
speed up its reform pace.
</P>
<P>
The law, issued in the form of emergency decree, is aimed to
restructure businesses by closing, selling or equitizing those in
the red.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry of Privatization, set up in November, will work
out policies and strategies to coordinate and control the whole
process of privatization.
</P>
<P>
The ministry will also list state-run enterprises to be
privatized, set a deadline for completion of the privatization
process and classify the businesses.
</P>
<P>
Under the country's constitution, an emergency decree takes
effect once it is announced. But the parliament can veto it if it
is considered inappropriate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
