<HEADLINE> Okinawa Residents Oppose Offshore Heliport Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The majority of local residents
in Japan's northern Okinawan city of Nago have voted against the
proposed construction of a sea-based U.S. military heliport, local
press reports said Monday.
</P>
<P>
In a referendum held Sunday, a total of 16,639 Nago residents
voted against the proposed 1,500-meter-long offshore heliport,
topping the 14,267 residents who supported the plan.
</P>
<P>
The offshore facility was aimed at relocating the heliport
operations of the U.S. Marine Corps' Futenma Air Station in
Ginowan, also in Okinawa Prefecture.
</P>
<P>
Although the outcome of the referendum is not legally binding,
Nago Mayor Tetsuya Higa said he would take the results into
consideration when deciding on whether to allow the heliport to be
built.
</P>
<P>
"I respect the feelings behind both the approval and
disapproval votes and will examine the results closely," Higa said.
</P>
<P>
Higa is expected to consult Okinawa Governor Masahide Ota this
month on the prefectural government's judgment on the heliport
construction issue before making his own decision.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto said earlier that the
government would not go ahead with the project without local
consent.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the outcome of the referendum, Asahi Shimbun, a
leading Japanese newspaper, said in an editorial that the central
government needs to abide by the voices of the majority.
</P>
<P>
Asahi's view was echoed by Mainichi Shimbun, another
mass-circulated newspaper, which said that both the mayor of Nago
and the Okinawa governor should cherish the voting results.
</P>
</TEXT>
