<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan Tamil Parties to Contest Polls Separately </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Five major Tamil parties in
Sri Lanka have decided to contest the Northern local elections
individually after their efforts to consider a joint boycott or to
contest on a joint list ended in failure Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The decision came after leaders of the Tamil United Liberation
Front (TULF), the Eelam People's Democratic Party (EPDP), the
People's Liberation Organization of Tamil Eelam (PLOTE), the Tamil
Eelam Liberation Organization (TELO) and the Eelam People's
Revolutionary Liberation Front (EPRLF) failed to reach a consensus
at Sunday's joint meeting, the official newspaper Daily News said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The paper said the party leaders are to complete their
nomination lists and file the papers Monday or Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Nomination of candidates, which began on December 16, ends on
December 23. The date of the elections is not available yet.
</P>
<P>
All the five parties are contesting the Jaffna Municipal
Council.
</P>
<P>
The TULF has announced that Sarojini Yogeswaran, widow of the
slain Jaffna MP V. Yogeswaran, will be its candidate for the
Jaffna mayoralty. The PLOTE nominated its deputy president, N.
Manikkathasan, as its mayoral candidate.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the ruling People's Alliance (PA) has decided not to
contest the polls in order to avoid any accusation of favoritism
by the army.
</P>
<P>
The main opposition party, the United National Party, also
decided not to run.
</P>
<P>
Many Tamil parties had hoped the government would postpone the
polls in the north until the situation there turns conducive to
elections.
</P>
<P>
They had argued that the current situation in the region cannot
ensure a free and fair election. Displaced persons, particularly
the Muslims, have not been able to resettle in their hometowns
while people within the Jaffna district cannot move freely due to
various restrictions, they claimed.
</P>
<P>
Sri Lanka held its local government elections in all but
Northern Province and parts of Eastern Province in March this
year. The local elections had been scheduled for 1995 but were
postponed twice for security reasons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
