<DOCNO> XIE19971222.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yearender: NATO in Between 1997 and 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The spring and summer of 1997
will be remembered as a formative period for NATO.
</P>
<P>
But the world's largest military alliance needs to justify its
attempt to grow larger in the post Cold War era.
</P>
<P>
Between May and July 1997, the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization (NATO) was crammed with a hectic calendar rife with
brow-lifting events including the signing of the NATO-Russia
Founding Act, the founding of the Euro-Atlantic Partnership
Council and the invitation of three former Warsaw Pact members to
join their former foes.
</P>
<P>
For NATO, all seemed to be faring in accordance with its will,
except for one thing: a reasonable justification for its desire to
enlarge when Cold War hostility has become something of memory and
when most allied countries are concentrating on their coffers,
since they are strapped by economic austerity measures.
</P>
<P>
What is desperately needed is a persuasive explanation for the
reason why the self-defense oriented NATO is expanding in spite of
the fact that there is no visible nemesis to fend off.
</P>
<P>
Without justification, further enlargement will have to remain
in question even though the legislators of allied nations have
ratified the inclusion of Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic
into the alliance.
</P>
<P>
Now that NATO has disclosed that its planned expansion will
cost no more than 1.3 billion U.S. dollars over 10 years for the
present 16 member states and the three new ones, the ratification,
slated for early next year, seemed in a position to turn out
easier parliamentary formalities.
</P>
<P>
The three east European countries will be expected to spend up
to 3.5 billion dollars of their own funds over the first two years
after accession to upgrade their armed forces and equipment to
NATO standards.
</P>
<P>
Previously, however, the U.S. Congressional Budget Office and
the U.S. Department of Defense offered two enlargement cost
estimates, ranging from 27 billion to as much as 125 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Their astronomical figures enraged their European allies that
argued back that the end of the tense nuclear standoff of the Cold
War meant the end of the need for a mighty allied military force
drawn up across Europe and facing eastward.
</P>
<P>
Washington was accused by some European governments of pushing
the enlargement agenda to benefit such U.S. defense industry
giants as Boeing, Raytheon and Lockheed-Martin Marietta.
</P>
<P>
In November 1991, NATO adopted a new strategic concept and
worked out guidelines for restructuring internally and externally.
</P>
<P>
Smaller, more multinational and more mobile formations were to
be substituted for the large national army corps. In June last
year, NATO set up a Combined Joint Task Force (CJTF), which is a
multinational and multi-service (including all four services of
land, sea, air and support) task force, capable of rapid
deployment to even beyond-NATO areas in the event of crises caused
by nationalism, religion, ethnics, environment and socio-economy.
</P>
<P>
In late November this year, the CJTF tested the command
capability of its headquarters as the final fine-tuning of its
year-long formation.
</P>
<P>
The CJTF command trial was a fictitious United Nations-mandated
peace-keeping operation in a made-up peninsula protruding off the
southeastern corner of Africa into the Indian Ocean. The
computerized African expedition was different in nature from the
peace-keeping missions in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1991 strategic concept has weakened the common
commitment by member states and national interests have taken
over, NATO has to reconsider a shift of strategic emphasis once
more.
</P>
<P>
Warren Christopher and William Perry, two veterans of U.S.
President Bill Clinton's first-term cabinet and both instrumental
in designing the enlargement, stressed that it is a strategic
imperative that NATO shift emphasis from defense of members'
territory to defense of common interests.
</P>
<P>
The North Atlantic Assembly, a consensus-building vanguard of
the Western military alliance as NATO chief Javier Solana put it,
reached an agreement at its 43rd annual session in October that
NATO has to revise its strategic concept to justify its existence
and development.
</P>
<P>
Parliamentarians from NATO nations agreed in Bucharest that the
alliance has to redefine the events that could lead up in future
to NATO actions, especially actions responsive to non-Article V
events.
</P>
<P>
Such a revision of strategic concept means an entirely new NATO
Charter. In Article V, the existing charter pledges that joint
action can be taken only when any one of the member states is
attacked. Such an attack should be taken as an attack on all
member states.
</P>
<P>
Only after it revises the self-defining charter will NATO have
sensible and suitable military reason to develop as well as
exist. A revision can best be expected around April 1999, when
NATO celebrates its 50th anniversary and winds up the formative
period set off by the hectic activities in this past spring and
summer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971222.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
