<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Acts to Prevent Kids From Lead Poisoning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Doctors in the Chinese capital
Beijing are conducting blood tests on children in the kindergartens
to find out whether they have too much lead in their blood.
</P>
<P>
The massive health check was triggered off by a recent survey
in Beijing which shows that 69.6 percent of the children randomly
selected for the blood testing have more lead in their body than
medically permitted.
</P>
<P>
Experts pointed out that children are most vulnerable to lead
poisoning. Auto emission, paints, some writing materials such as
pencils and crayons, even some snacks such as pop corns can be the
culprits.
</P>
<P>
Children with minor lead-poisoning can have behavior and
learning problems. They tend to be restless, aggressive and
short-tempered and more prone to illness including cold and
anemia.
</P>
<P>
Doctors plan to use non-medicine method to treat the
lead-affected children and are calling for reinforced prevention
efforts.
</P>
<P>
Currently some 170 nurses in the kindergartens from the city's 18
suburban counties and townships are receiving special training in
this regard.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971222.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
