<HEADLINE> Tianjin to Adopt Unemployment Warning System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Tianjin, the largest
industrial city in north China, plans to adopt an unemployment
warning system to strengthen macro-control of its job
market.
</P>
<P>
The system will use the city's unemployment rate and employment
situation as the major monitoring indicators to update information
concerning the job market.
</P>
<P>
Some 60,000 workers in the city have lost jobs during the
ongoing reform in state-owned enterprises, and the municipal
government has responsed by adopting measures to help them
return to work.
</P>
<P>
The warning system will help strengthen management of the
city's urban and rural labor resources. An information collection
system will also be established to improve control over the labor
flow.
</P>
<P>
A research program has been carried out to determine an
acceptable unemployment rate for the city, and the municipal
government has set a goal of helping more than 80 percent of
laid-off workers find new jobs.
</P>
<P>
By the end of this year, Tianjin will open labor management
offices in all its districts and over 50 percent of its
townships. 
</P>
</TEXT>
