<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inner Mongolia Projects End Drinking Water Shortages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Water supply projects now
enable 4.5 million farmers and herdsmen in Inner Mongolia to drink
as much water as they want.
</P>
<P>
The projects have also ended the long-standing water shortage
affecting over 13.44 million head of livestock in the region.
</P>
<P>
Inadequate drinking water supply facilities and a nomadic way
of life have long forced people living in the vast grasslands in
Inner Mongolia to rely on inadequate rainfall and melting
snow. The water shortage is even more severe during droughts.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1995, the drive to build water supply facilities
had removed drinking water shortages for more than three million
people and 10 million head of livestock.
</P>
<P>
A plan adopted in 1996 will solve drinking water shortages for
the remaining 3.8 million people and over 12 million head of
livestock by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The central, regional and local governments have invested 150
million yuan (18.07 million US dollars) to construct 11,828 water
supply projects which now supply drinking water to one million
people and 2.23 million head of livestocks.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
