<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila to Borrow for Higher Foreign Reserves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of the
Philippines is planning to borrow 500 million U.S. dollars to
boost its dwindling foreign reserves in order to defend the local
currency from speculation.
</P>
<P>
The gross international reserves (GIR) was reduced to 9.7
billion dollars last week from 10.2 billion dollars in October due
to its massive intervention in the local currency market during
the period, local press reports Monday quoted Central Bank
Governor Gabriel Singson as saying.
</P>
<P>
The central bank has received offers from many global
investment bankers to underwrite medium- or long-term bond
issuances to boost its GIR, Singson said.
</P>
<P>
"I think we must start building our war chest, just in case,"
Singson said of the need to reinforce the country's present
holdings of foreign exchange, mostly U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Singson said the most obvious source of foreign funds right now
is the International Monetary Fund from which the central bank may
get 345 million dollars, the last tranche of the Extended Fund
Facility (EFF) the IMF promised to the country.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines is also entitled to receive a parallel
financing facility from Japan Export and Import Bank (Jexim)
amounting to some 300 million dollars if the country meets all the
requirements tied to the EFF program.
</P>
<P>
Singson said he is optimistic the IMF and Jexim will release
the funds after the country graduates from the IMF's EFF program
in January next year.
</P>
<P>
The GIR consists of the central bank's total assets in foreign
exchange. A higher GIR level reflects a government's greater
ability to finance the country's imports and meet foreign
obligations.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
