<HEADLINE> Shenzhen Plan Calls for More Attention to Quality </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Shenzhen, China's first
economic zone, has formulated a plan to improve quality in the
building industry and service trades to become more competitive in
the international market.
</P>
<P>
The city, located in south China's Guangdong Province, will
popularize the ISO9000 quality standard among enterprises,
according to the plan.
</P>
<P>
Every year, 100 enterprises in the city will be encouraged to
qualify for the ISO9000 quality certification under the plan.
</P>
<P>
The plan's goals call for 80 percent of major industrial
products to be up to international standards by the end of the
year 2000, and 80 percent of building enterprises and all
enterprises involving the field of foreign service trades will get
ISO9000 certification by the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
Local statistics show that 85 percent of products are up to the
national standards, higher than the national average.
</P>
<P>
The plan will also push the city's foreign trade forward, said
the local government.
</P>
<P>
The city is expected to earn 24 billion U.S. dollars in exports
this year, an increase of 13.2 percent over last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
