<DOCNO> XIE19971222.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aging Stars Put Europe Back in Contention (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Speed and agility may have
diminished with the years. But the technique remains and hunger
is still growing in both Jan-Ove Waldner and Zoran Primorac,
winners of the most conveted table tennis honors in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The two veterans well past their primes ruined an otherwise
perfect year for China, putting Europe back into fray with the
table tennis powerhouse which had swept all major titles in the
past two years.
</P>
<P>
The 31-year-old Swede, whose last men's world singles title
came in 1989, denied China a once-again seven-title sweep by
edging Chinese out of the top two and demoralizing upstart
Vladimir Samsonov in the final which turned from a predictedly
even game to a one-man show.
</P>
<P>
Primorac, 28, the backbone of Yugoslavia's 1991 world
runners-up squad and now a role model in Croatia, added the World
Cup to his China Open title despite the conflict in war-torn
Yugoslavia had for quite long time made his training sporadic.
</P>
<P>
China showed its matchless depth by bagging six gold medals in
the Manchester world championships in May, where diminutive Deng
Yaping lifted her ninth title to become the most-crowned in the
table tennis history.
</P>
<P>
Six, a lucky number for the Chinese, didn't make their players
happy. It was the men's singles championship that China wanted to
get most.
</P>
<P>
The 21-year-old Samsonov put Belarus into the world map of
table tennis by beating China's 1995 world champion and World Cup
winner Kong Linghui for the first time in their four encounters.
Waldner snatched the other final spot with an easy win over
another Chinese Yan Sen.
</P>
<P>
Waldner, the only male player to have won a Grand Slam of the
Olympic, world championship and World Cup singles honors, crushed
Samsonov in a ruthless demonstration of who was the best in the
world.
</P>
<P>
The immensely experienced Swede revenged his 6-21, 7-21 team
match loss to Samsonov, beating his rival in straight sets to
take the most coveted singles championship after a hiatus of
eight years.
</P>
<P>
"It's like a title bout of the world best heavyweights," said
Swedish head coach Ulf Carlsson. "Jan-Ove knocked out Vladimir."
</P>
<P>
Waldner after the match tipped Samsonov as next in line to the
throne.
</P>
<P>
But Samsonov's run to the top was delayed by hand injuries and
a series of listless outings.
</P>
<P>
The Belarussian, who beat four Chinese in a row to enter the
world championship final, has been struggling a little since. He
lost in the Japan Open to Wang Liqin, in the China Open to Ma Lin
and to Kong Linghui in the World Cup semi-finals in October, the
three Chinese he had defeated in Manchester.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971222.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aging Stars Put Europe Back in Contention (2-last) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Primorac, the World Cup winner in 1993 and 1997, was holding
the European standard in the second half of this year.
</P>
<P>
In October's World Cup, world number six Primorac beat Kong
Linghui to take the 36,000-dollar winner check without losing a
set in six matches.
</P>
<P>
Primorac believed it was mental strength that carried him
through to the World Cup title. "I felt once the match got close
I could still win -- I had a lot of confidence," he said.
</P>
<P>
It was a continuation of regained form which saw him win the
China Open in September and reach the finals of the European
Masters Cup and Brazilian Open.
</P>
<P>
Kong, who had fame thrust on him at an early age, was not
disgraced by finishing second. Had Kong won, it would have been
China's 11th World Cup out of 18 dating back to 1980.
</P>
<P>
The 22-year-old Chinese won the doubles event with Olympic
singles-doubles champion Liu Guoliang after pacing China to its
12th team championship in Manchester.
</P>
<P>
After the World Cup, China once again sounded the alarm.
</P>
<P>
"In the men's table tennis, Chinese have no advantage over
Europeans," warned Xu Yinsheng, the head of the Chinese Table
Tennis Association who is also the president of ITTF, the world
ruling body for the sport.
</P>
<P>
"There is the writing on the wall," he said, "Chinese have to
improve on their skills and toughen their mentality."
</P>
<P>
Primorac agreed with Xu in part. "We can compete with Chinese
individually but none of the European nations is a match for
China," he said.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, the World Cup holder called for a Ryder Cup style
format in table tennis to make men's team events more competitive
against China.
</P>
<P>
"In team events it's very hard to beat China and I think they
will dominate for the next 10 years. But I think if we had a
European team, we could beat them," Primorac said.
</P>
<P>
Like in golf's Ryder Cup, where Europe beat the United States
14.5 to 13.5 in September, the event became more competitive once
the British and Irish joined force with mainland Europe.
</P>
<P>
Primorac noted there was some hope for European players
because they in general had better backhands.
</P>
<P>
"Some of the Chinese penhold players have weak backhands which
is a major disadvantage," he said.
</P>
<P>
China's desperate save of the traditional penhold style paid
off in 1996 as it finally produced a double Olympic champion in
Liu Guoliang, who sticks rubber onto both sides of the bat and
plays topspins with backhand.
</P>
<P>
Feng Zhe and Ma Lin, who both play like Liu, upset Waldner and
Samsonov respectively in the China Open, winning the praise that
China had succeeded in evolution of the style which had once been
regarded as a dying art.
</P>
<P>
"The two youngsters's victories were significant to the
Chinese traditional style," Chinese head coach Cai Zhenhua
said. "We have improved a lot on penholders' backhand offensive
and power."
</P>
<P>
Whereas the Chinese men had been struggling in barrages by
Europeans, their women players still ruled the roost in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese women's team, led by four-time Olympic champion
Deng Yaping, clean-swept the women's titles in the Manchester
Worlds.
</P>
<P>
Wang Nan, world championship runner-up to Deng, snatched the
World Cup in September in absence of her awesome teammate.
</P>
<P>
The year-end world rankings may as well serve as a testimony
of the Chinese women's strength. Seven of the top ten are
Chinese, with the others former Chinese nationals now playing for
their adopted countries or regions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971222.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
