<HEADLINE> Chairman of Maccabiah Games Resign Over Bridge Collapse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 21 (Xinhua) -- The Chairman of the
Maccabiah Games and an aide resigned Sunday over the collapse of a
bridge at the 1997 Maccabiah games in Israel.
</P>
<P>
Four Australians were killed and dozens injured when the bridge
over the Yarkon river collapsed on July 14 when members of the
Australian team were crossing during the opening ceremony for the
15th games, the Jewish Olympics.
</P>
<P>
Maccabiah chairman Yoram Eyal and Itamar Herman, who was
responsible for the opening ceremony, announced their resignations
at a meeting of international organizers of the games, including
delegates from Australia.
</P>
<P>
The special meeting of the World Maccabiah Union was called to
discuss a decision by Israeli prosecutors to indict five people on
charges of negligence and reckless endangerment over the bridge
collapse.
</P>
<P>
Eyal is among the five, along with the contractors and engineer
who built the bridge.
</P>
<P>
Two Australian athletes drowned and two others died from the
effects of swallowing the polluted water in the Yarkon river.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
