<HEADLINE> Greek Parliament Approves 1998 Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, December 22 (Xinhua) -- The Greek Parliament has just
approved the 1998 budget which aims at consolidating the country's
economic stability.
</P>
<P>
The budget, which had already been adopted by the Greek cabinet
last month, was also expected to enable the country to reach the
targets set by the government for joining Europe's Economic and
Monetary Union (EMU).
</P>
<P>
Under the budget, consumer price inflation, currently 4.7
percent, would fall to 2.5 percent by the end of 1998, and
unemployment, now 9.7 percent, to 9.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The deficit was planned to drop down to 2.4 percent, while the
GDP growth rate will increase from the present 3.5 percent to 3.7
percent.
</P>
<P>
The budget was passed by 163 votes in favor and 136 votes
against shortly after midnight. 
</P>
</TEXT>
