<DOCNO> XIE19971222.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lankan President Supports Indo-Pak talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lankan President
Chandrika Kumaratunga said here Sunday that her country supports
the process of dialogue between Pakistan and India to address
their contentious issues.
</P>
<P>
"We hope the talks will move forward even if they don't
progress as fast as we like," she said.
</P>
<P>
The president, who arrived here Saturday for a three-day
official visit, noted that Pakistan has always expressed the
desire to resolve the issues with India through dialogue.
</P>
<P>
She denied that members of the South Asian Association for
Regional Cooperation (SAARC) are trying to form blocks within the
organization.
</P>
<P>
"No, we don't need to form blocks within SAARC, there is
nothing we can't resolve within ourselves through dialogue," she
said in response to a question after delivering a speech titled
"South Asia: Into Next Century" at the Institute of Regional
Studies.
</P>
<P>
Chandrika said earlier in her speech that the political
dialogue initiated between New Delhi and Islamabad was greeted by
the other member States of SAARC, "with relief and undisguised
optimism."
</P>
<P>
The current political confidence among South Asian States, she
said, has developed to a remarkable degree if contrasted with the
situation which prevailed in the early days of SAARC, which groups
Sri Lanka, India, Pakistan, Bangladesh, Nepal, Bhutan and the
Maldives.
</P>
<P>
"Cold War postures have melted or appear less threatening," she
said, adding that "issues that once divided us can now be seen
with greater clarity and addressed more directly"
</P>
<P>
She hoped that SAARC may in time even be able to deal
collectively with the remaining political issues that stand in the
way of progress.
</P>
<P>
She also noted that economic activity in SAARC needs to be
widened to include joint ventures, intra-regional investment,
technological exchanges, tourism promotion and joint services.
</P>
<P>
While each state in South Asia has to come to terms
individually with the globalization process, taking into account
its own needs and capacities, it would be better equipped to face
the harsh realities of the market place if these realities could
be approached collectively. "Here I see an important role for
SAARC."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
