<HEADLINE> Nigeria Aborts Coup, Arrests Abacha's Deputy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria has aborted a coup
attempting to topple military ruler General Sani Abacha and
arrested his deputy, Lieutenant-General Oladipo Diya, for his role
in it, a senior military officer said on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Major-General Abdulsalam Abubakar, an aide to Oladipo Diya,
told Xinhua they foiled the plot early in the morning and arrested
seven other senior officers.
</P>
<P>
The other coup plotters included former Minister of Works and
Housing Major-General Abul-Karim Adisa and former Minister of
Communications Major-General Tajudeen Olanrewaju, both of whom
were sacked in the cabinet reshuffle in November.
</P>
<P>
The aide said the capital city Abuja was calm.
</P>
<P>
A televised statement said: "The Federal Government wishes to
assure law abiding citizens that it will strongly resist any
attempt to undermine the security and integrity of the nation."
</P>
<P>
Abacha, 54, an infantry general coming from the largely
Hausa-speaking north, took control of Africa's most populous
nation in the political turmoil which followed the 1993 poll.
</P>
<P>
The history of oil-producing Nigeria has been recorded with
military coup attempts and alleged plots. Civilians have held
power for only 10 years since Nigeria won independence from
Britain in 1960. 
</P>
</TEXT>
