<HEADLINE> Guangxi-Taiwan Economic Cooperation Growing Fast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING December 22 (Xinhua) -- Taiwan has invested 1.2 billion
U.S. dollars to establish 706 enterprises in south China's Guangxi
Zhuang Autonomous Region and become the second largest investor in
the region after Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Thirty percent of these investments are in light industry; 25
percent in real estate, tourism and catering; and the remainder in
such industries as machinery, agriculture and forestry, breeding,
building materials, chemical industry, medicine and
high-technology, said Lu Chi, the local official in charge of
Taiwan affairs.
</P>
<P>
Lu said 49 percent of the Taiwan-funded enterprises are joint
ventures, 15 percent are co-operatives and 36 percent are wholly
Taiwan-funded.
</P>
<P>
The region has attracted 71 Taiwan-funded enterprises in
agricultural production involving a total contractual investment
of 70 million U.S. dollars, Lu said.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan has also invested in poor areas of the region as well as
in the cities of Nanning, Liuzhou, Guizhou and Beihai.
</P>
<P>
With the purpose of introducing more funds and technologies,
the local government has formulated a number of preferential
policies and made efforts to improve the infrastructure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
