<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mayer Wins in Alta Badia Giant Slalom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Christian Mayer of Austria
claimed the victory in the World Cup giant slalom in Alta Badia,
Italy on Sunday after Italian legend Alberto Tomba crashed out of
the second try.
</P>
<P>
Mayer, the 1994 Olympic bronze medallist at Lillehammer and who
was leading after the first run, clocked a combined time of two
minutes 20.97 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Switzerland's Michael Von Gruenigen, who had been hoping for
his third victory in four races, had to settle for second place in
2:21.40, while Austria's overall World Cup leader Hermann Maier
was third in 2:21.63.
</P>
<P>
It was another devastating victory for the Austrian ski
machine, which after filling the top five places in the second
downhill at Beaver Creek, filled seven of the top eight places
here.
</P>
<P>
The biggest loser of the day was Tomba, who had won in Alta
Badia four times before and had been promising his fans a
Christmas present, either at Alta Badia or at Madonna di Campiglio
in Monday's slalom.
</P>
<P>
Organisers spent more than five minutes working on the piste
before Tomba went down, after he had moved up to sixth place in
the first run, having started with bib number 19.
</P>
<P>
But the triple Olympic champion, who had complained about the
state of the piste after the first run, lost his balance
completely after half a minute of the second. He just about
managed to stay upright but promptly straddled a gate with his
legs wide apart. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971222.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central China Using Satellites To Reduce Flood Threat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, December 22 (Xinhua) -- Central China's Hunan
Province will try to use satellites to reduce the effect of
flooding in the Dongting Lake area, according to experts at a
recent Sino-French seminar here.
</P>
<P>
A satellite system is expected to be operating by May, 1998 for
the lake area, which has 700,000 ha of farmland and 10 million
people. It is a key grain area that generates a third of the
province's agricultural output value, also an important industrial
center on the middle reaches of the Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
The lake has had flood disasters in 37 years since the country
was founded in 1949, and China began to use meteorology satellites
to forecast floods in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
One professor who has studied the phenomenon all that time,
says that it is now the time to establish a better satellite
system. The new system will forecast floods, and also provide
information on how to resume production after the disaster.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19971222.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
