<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0030 GMT, December 22 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS -- The second Athens meeting on the Middle East peace
process ended Sunday with a declaration calling for the speedy
implementation of the agreements signed by Israel and Palestine.
</P>
<P>
In the Athens declaration, participants from Palestine and
Israel expressed their deep concern at the current state of the
peace process, calling on their leaderships to meet regularly in
order to defuse tension and build confidence.
</P>
<P>
They urged both Israel and Palestine and to work towards the
establishment of a joint monitoring committee with international
participation, to make sure that there was a full respect of and
adherence to the already signed agreements, and implement an
interim agreement that would facilitate the final status
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States Defense Secretary William Cohen
said Sunday that his nation pursues diplomatic channels to
pressure Iraq to allow U.N. inspectors access to suspected weapons
sites.
</P>
<P>
"We hope to pursue this in diplomatic channels and see if we
can't exhaust all reasonable opportunities to do that," Cohen said
on the CBS program "Face the Nation."
</P>
<P>
Iraq has banned the U.N. Special Commission in charge of
dismantling the country's weapons of mass destruction from
checking presidential sites. It insists that no weapons are hidden
at those locations.
</P>
<P>
Iraq said that it would never allow any inspection to its
presidential sites, which it regards as vital to its national
security and sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY -- The ongoing summit of the Gulf Cooperation
Council (GCC) Sunday agreed on the political issues which will be
touched in its final communique, sources close to the summit said.
</P>
<P>
The final communique of the summit may include political issues
such as ties between GCC member states with Iran, situations in
Iraq and the Middle East peace process, according to the sources.
</P>
<P>
They said the leaders of the six GCC Arab states have formed a
joint stand on relations with Iran.
</P>
<P>
The final communique is expected to call on Iran to solve its
dispute with the United Arab Emirates (UAE) on the three islands
of Greater Tunb, Lesser Tunb and Abu Musa in the Gulf by peaceful
means, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Iran has been making efforts to improve the relations with its
Arab neighbors. The Islamic summit held on December 9-11 in Iran
set a stage for it to push for the goal. Iran's President Mohammed
Khatami expressed readiness last week to visit the UAE to discuss
the dispute. 
</P>
</TEXT>
