<HEADLINE> Eastern Chinese Province Making Progress In Animal Husbandry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, December 22 (Xinhua) -- East China's Anhui Province has
high expectations for its animal husbandry, according to an
agriculture official, who explains that an expansion program that
began early last year increased meat output by 2.35 million tons
and egg output by 675,000 tons by the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the industry contributed 56.2 yuan to each farmer on
average, accounting for a fifth of the per-capita net income
increase last year.
</P>
<P>
The province plans to increase 4.5 to five million tons in
animal husbandry output by the end of this century, the official
says. It is expected to generate 23 billion yuan in annual output
value by that time, and it will contribute over 1,000 yuan to the
annual income of each farmer.
</P>
<P>
The province's meat output in the first ten months of this year
was 2.21 million tons, and 703,000 tons for eggs, up 18.7 percent
and 16 percent respectively from the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
In the past two years, the sector has obtained 13 million yuan
(1.5 million U.S. dollars) in government funding for 16 new
breeding bases, so that it can generate 72 percent of the
province's animal husbandry production.  
</P>
</TEXT>
