<HEADLINE> U.S. Government Launches Anti-Drug Campaign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 21 (Xinhua) -- The Clinton administration
today launched a 195 million U.S. dollars campaign to reinforce
the prevention of youths from abusing illicit drugs.
</P>
<P>
The program will be carried out in 12 cities for four months.
Anti-drug ads will run everywhere children aged 9 to 17 are likely
to be watching, from television to the Internet, General Barry
McCaffrey, director of the Office of National Drug Control Policy,
said.
</P>
<P>
The ads are to be tested from January through April in Atlanta,
Baltimore, Boise, Denver, Hartford, Houston, Milwaukee, Portland,
San Diego, Sioux City, Tucson and Washington.
</P>
<P>
"Today's announcement marks the January initiation of a
multifaceted national campaign that will harness the energies of
parents, mass media, corporate America and the anti-drug
coalitions to halt and reverse the disturbing rise in drug use
among young people," McCaffrey said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
President Clinton in a radio address Saturday called on parents
to make efforts to prevent children from abusing drugs.
</P>
<P>
A survey released Saturday shows that Marijuana use is still on
the rise among 10th and 12th graders in the nation. The
12th-graders who use illicit drugs, including marijuana, cocaine,
heroin and hallucinogens, increased from 27.1 percent in 1992 to
40.2 percent in 1996 and further to 42.2 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
Among the eight-graders, a 1991 survey showed that 6.2 percent
reported smoking marijuana in the prior year. But by 1996, the
percentage rose to 18.3. However, this year's study found that the
percentage dropped to 17.7. 
</P>
</TEXT>
