<HEADLINE> "No Change" in UK Stance on Prisoners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 21 (Xinhua) - British Prime Minister Tony
Blair and his Irish counterpart Bertie Ahern held a 45-minute
meeting to discuss the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders met at the Newcastle United/Manchester United
football match at St James's Park today.
</P>
<P>
It is understood all aspects of the peace process were raised.
But there was no indication of a British shift toward release of
pro-British prisoners jailed for sectarian violence, Irish
officials were quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Pro-British unionist parties in Northern Ireland were upset
last week over Dublin's release of nine IRA guerrillas from prison
before completing their sentences.
</P>
<P>
Ahead of his meeting with Blair, Ahern told reporters that
releases of prisoners from both sides of the political divide were
an "essential confidence-building measure" in the peace process.
