<DOCNO> XIE19971222.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Foreign Minister to Visit UAE </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Minister
Kamal Kharrazi will pay an official visit to the United Arab
Emirates (UAE) in the near future, an Iranian newspaper
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The paper Jomhuri Eslami (Islamic Republic) reported that
Kharrazi would arrive in Abu Dhabi after the end of the
summit of the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) which was opened
in Kuwait Saturday.
</P>
<P>
It was believed that the main agenda for Kharrazi's visit
to the UAE would be the territorial dispute over the three
islands of Abu Musa, the greater and lesser Tunbs at the
mouth of the strategic strait of Hormuz.
</P>
<P>
Both Tehran and Abu Dhabi claimed full sovereignty over the
islands despite their agreement to co-rule the islands in the
Gulf following the British withdrawal from the region in 1971.
</P>
<P>
Following the May presidential elections in iran, the
government of President Mohammad Khatami took initiatives to show
its goodwill gestures to the GCC states and Kharrazi made a tour
to the six countries in November.
</P>
<P>
The GCC members also voiced their readiness to improve ties
with Iran and their leaders have started their discussion on
relations with Tehran at the ongoing GCC summit.
</P>
<P>
Reports reaching here said the GCC members were also
encouraged by the United States to improve relations with
Iran. Washington claimed that the rapprochement between Iran and
the GCC states would have no impact on Washington's close
relations with the Gulf Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
In Tehran, the Iranian daily Tehran Times today urged the
ongoing GCC summit to adopt a new policy toward Iran under
the new atmosphere, particularly after the eighth Islamic summit
held in Tehran on December 9-11.
</P>
<P>
Khatami has said that Iran is ready to settle the
misunderstandings with the UAE through negotiations at any level,
the daily said, hoping the GCC to help settle the
"misunderstandings in an amicable atmosphere." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
