<HEADLINE> Athens Middle East Peace Process Meeting Ends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
ATHENS, December 21 (Xinhua) -- The second Athens meeting on the
Middle East peace process ended today with a declaration calling for
the speedy implementation of the agreements signed by Israel and
Palestine.
</P>
<P>
In the Athens declaration, participants from Palestine and
Israel expressed their deep concern at the current state of the
peace process, calling on their leaderships to meet regularly in
order to defuse tension and build confidence.
</P>
<P>
They urged both Israel and Palestine and to work towards the
establishment of a joint monitoring committee with international
participation, to make sure that there was a full respect of and
adherence to the already signed agreements, and implement an interim
agreement that would facilitate the final status negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The participants also called for the establishment of appropriate
conditions, conducive to Palestinian economic development, the
lifting of closures, for open borders and freedom of movement, which
would, in turn, create economic and other links between the West
Bank and Gaza and Israel.
</P>
<P>
The four-day meeting, which was held behind closed doors, was
attended by members of the Palestinian authority and of the
Legislative Council, two vice presidents of the Israeli Knesset and
deputies from both the Israeli coalition and opposition.
</P>
<P>
The first Athens meeting on the Middle East peace process took
place in July this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
