<HEADLINE> 2 Greek Diplomats Ordered to Leave Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Turkey had ordered two Greek
diplomats to leave the country under the accusation of being
involved in espionage, a local private television station reported
today.
</P>
<P>
Greek Military Attache Efstratios Haralambous and an
administrative official at the Greek consulate in Turkey's largest
city of Istanbul were accused of spying for Turkey's outlawed
Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK), the report said.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting since 1984 against the government for
autonomy in eastern and southeastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the Turkish National Intelligence
Organization had been shadowing the Greek military attache and
discovered he was spying for the PKK.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Foreign Ministry had summoned Greek Ambassador in
Ankara Dimitris Nezeritis and told him that Haralambous was
involved in "acts outside his official duty" and asked him to
leave the country.
</P>
<P>
Greece today denied Turkey's accusation.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has accused Greece of supporting the PKK and allowing it
to establish mobile training camps on its soil. But Greece has
rejected the charge.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Greece, both NATO members, have long been at odds
over several issues including the limits of air space and the
Aegean Sea, rights to sea-bed minerals and the Cyprus problem.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
