<DOCNO> XIE19971222.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-12-21 21:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt's Luxor Police Chiefs Stand Trial for Neglect </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 21 (Xinhua) -- Four police officers in charge
of the security in Luxor today stood trial for dereliction of duty
in the terrorist attack in the southern Egyptian city last month.
</P>
<P>
On trial at the Primary Disciplinary Council are Colonel Amr
Ahmed Agour, First Lieutenants Ibrahim Mohamed Al Saady and Sherif
Afifi, officers at the General Directorate of Luxor Police, and Lt.
Colonel Sherif Gamal Thabet, Chief of the Antiquities Section.
</P>
<P>
They were charged of "gross negligence and laxity" and failure
to lay down plans for securing historical sites in Egypt's largest
archeological city from terrorist attacks, the Middle East News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The charges leveled against them were based on the fact
that they neglected their duties, despite their awareness through
intelligence reports that terrorists were targeting such sites
and their visitors, said the MENA.
</P>
<P>
All of the four defendants pleaded not guilty. They face
penalties of notice, dismissal, warning, suspension, cut in
salaries or acquittal. They have the right to appeal before the
Higher Police Council and the State Council.
</P>
<P>
The terrorist threats culminated in the November 17 attack when
six Islamic militants went on a shooting spree in front the
4,500-year-old Hatshepsut Temple, killing over 60 foreign tourists
and Egyptians. The area around the temple was guarded by only two
patrols and the police were slow to the rescue.
</P>
<P>
At the end of the 10-minute trial, the Council adjourned
hearings of the case until January 4. It also decided that the
next trial be a secret one.
</P>
<P>
The trial took place following investigations by the Inspection
and Control Sector of the Interior Ministry. After the incident,
Egypt has replaced its top security chief, kicked out a number of
senior police officers and revamped its security plans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
